commit_message:
Improve readability of JQ expression

Clean up JQ expressions to match style used elsewhere in the code.

Break up long lines.

Allow update in JQ rather than section replacement.

Output formatted JQ to disk.

Change-Id: I4deba620485df13454376cbb9fc20a904e33cc98

commit_message:
Move masquerade host_ip to config.json

Take the host IP for the masquerade iptables from config.json, which is merged
into the seed metadata. This allows the host_ip to be reconfigured later.

Change-Id: Ib0b69a464b6073894be5ee5203b0b8b6bb359fc7

commit_message:
Mark 'manager' as primary machine

Mark 'manager' as primary machine to be able to use commands like
'vagrant ssh' without specifiying the machine name.

This will solve the issue 'This command requires a specific VM name
to target in a multi-VM environment.'.

Change-Id: I15143d54d69dc05146aa141594924e30d18ba54e

The main goal of this blueprint is to define a hypervisor-agnostic interface
to notify applications of an impending snapshot and to perform any
application-specific quiesce operations prior to a filesystem freeze and
snapshot. A notification is also delivered when a snapshot and thaw have

commit_message:
Application Consistent Snapshot

The main goal of this blueprint is to define a hypervisor-agnostic interface
to notify applications of an impending snapshot and to perform any
application-specific quiesce operations prior to a filesystem freeze and
snapshot. A notification is also delivered when a snapshot and thaw have
completed in order for the application to perform any post-thaw operations.

Change-Id: Idbbdf759fd74c8300926dafb7d0817b64923bd4f

commit_message:
Do not use multiline strings for the 'stack_sshkey' option

Using multiline strings for the 'stack_sshkey' option results in the
following Puppt error:

Parameter key failed on Ssh_authorized_key[stack]: Key must not contain whitespace:

Change-Id: I41da285086af3fd90fb4887cd643d17ec52806a8

[{'account_id': 11154, 'date': '2014-09-29 18:36:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2014-09-29 18:36:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-09-29 19:11:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

(1 comment)

Hi,

I made a couple of comments on the commit message. However, I think this patch (and the referenced bug) is a duplicate of:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121745/6/nova/compute/manager.py,cm

As such, I'm marking this as -2. However, please let me know if I'm wrong and I'll lift it.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 11154, 'date': '2014-09-29 19:35:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Actually, you are correct.  This is a duplicate.

commit_message:
Add missing 'recreate' paramter to kwargs so that the flag
will be set correctly in the correct rebuild method.

The 'recreate' flag need to be set so that the called rebuild
method will preserve the user file system on an evacuate operation.

Change-Id: I7f3b6e3a1c49e0e591307f30e8d67b92f1726672
Closes-Bug: 1367523

commit_message:
Treat null values in JSON as being absent rather than 'None'

The current method of serialization for keys containing null
values in JSON input files is that they become a part of the
metadata tree, with a value expressed as the string 'None' in
output (when invoked with --key) or when inserted into templates.

The use of 'None' creates awkward ambiguity (no way for downstream
code logic to tell if the request JSON key originally contained
the string "None" or if it was actually null), and also throws
conversion errors when requested in any type other than 'raw'.

This patch proposes that keys with null values be handled as
though they were absent from the metadata completely. (If
such a key is requested in command-line invokations using "--key"
and "--key-default", the provided default will be printed.)

Change-Id: I9288dffb13d781e0c4dd9e5be0b483c090ec2d7c

commit_message:
Enable Swift resident Hive tables for EDP with the vanilla plugin

vanilla1 plugin supports Hive but Hive can't access Swift.
vanilla2 plugin not supports Hive.
This proposal aims that Hive can process the table that stored in Swift
and add hive support to vanilla2 plugin.

Change-Id: I804a4a309ecc308b11c65d3672c8ce912cb8d82a
Blueprint: edp-hive-vanilla-swift

commit_message:
Extended Vendor Passthru

This spec is about making the VendorPassthru and DriverVendorPassthru
consistent and extend it to support running vendor methods synchronously
and asynchronously as well as different HTTP methods apart from POST.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-28 19:30:28.000000000', 'message': "Don't replace OS::Neutron::Port on update

Due to an ununsual interface to OS::Neutron::Port resources,
it's necessary to specify replacement_policy: AUTO, or the
resource is unconditionally replaced on every stack update.

I've started discussion re possibly changing the default in
Heat, but right now, we need this or we have the bad outcome
of replacing all (!) compute and controller nodes on every
stack-update, even if the templates are unmodified.

Passing the AUTO value should be safe regardless of any
potential change of default value in Heat.

Change-Id: I6dd02ae17407f8f4c81ae418e5027f4f38ae4e9b
Closes-Bug: #1383709
"}]
commit_message:
Don't replace OS::Neutron::Port on update

Due to an ununsual interface to OS::Neutron::Port resources,
it's necessary to specify replacement_policy: AUTO, or the
resource is unconditionally replaced on every stack update.

I've started discussion re possibly changing the default in
Heat, but right now, we need this or we have the bad outcome
of replacing all (!) compute and controller nodes on every
stack-update, even if the templates are unmodified.

Passing the AUTO value should be safe regardless of any
potential change of default value in Heat.

Change-Id: I6dd02ae17407f8f4c81ae418e5027f4f38ae4e9b
Closes-Bug: #1383709

commit_message:
Link to os-cloud-config developer docs

Now that os-cloud-config's developer docs are in a state that I'm
happy with them being rather more discoverable, link to them in
openstack-projects.html, in a new section titled "OpenStack related
projects".

Change-Id: Ifb8b92e9b51ac968febde4b24334334323bf0638

commit_message:
Use wsgi.response for v2.1 API

Now a decorator @wsgi.response() can be used for specifying success
status code. Most v2.1 APIs use the decorator and it makes the code
more readable. This patch replaces webob.Response with the decorator
for the other APIs.
In addition, this patch changes some orders of decorators for showing
success code and expected error codes clearly.

Even if applying this patch, some webob.Response() calls still exist
under the path nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/ because these
cases need to contain some information in a response header.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I419819b8e55427979e8d82b972cd237952a5b06b

commit_message:
Link bug in requirements so people understand why pbr is listed

To make it more obvious why pbr is the first requirement in the file/s
add a link to the bug that caused this requirement to be re-added so
that for future prosperity/generations... it is known.

Change-Id: I11b23675cc379934e83b237bc30ca6baa0a87751

commit_message:
Update hooks from oslo-incubator copy

Collapse identical methods for pre/post into one method. Copy
over documentation as well. We are getting rid of oslo-incubator's
copy of hooks.py in the following change id, so from now on
nova has the only copy of this module

If55b37ccb20d9bc520909490f4f00de4ed430638

Change-Id: Ie43913fc847ee7ce247862f53c14a2daec433224

commit_message:
Deletes floating ip related connection states

When a floating ip is dissociated with a port, the current
connection with the floating ip is still working. This patch
will clear the connection state and cut off the connection
immediately.

Since conntrack -D will return 1, which is not an error code,
so add extra_ok_codes argument to execute methods.

Change-Id: Ia9bd7ae243a0859dcb97e2fa939f7d16f9c2456c
Closes-Bug: #1334926
(cherry picked from commit 966645538395079b5337b5ed30d597112279283c)

commit_message:
Support for server pools in minidns

notify_zone_changed and poll_for_serial_number
are now implemented.
Currently mdns has some temporary code to allow
both pool manager and central to call into it.  This
is to ensure that nothing breaks while the pool
manager is still under development.

Partially-implements: blueprint server-pools-minidns-support
Change-Id: I1977b4f910e986e876c9a4e07827d4f84a6cfd78

commit_message:
Autohelp: sanitize the value during discovery

Most of the default value sanitization happened during the docbook
writting, and not during the 'dump' of the options. This resulted in
invalid values in the xml files produced by diff_branches.py.

This patch moves all the sanitization code to the same function,
ensuring that the sanitization happens during options discovery.

Change-Id: I4d7e5d601baac5294937525ede8655da6b25e6cf

commit_message:
CORE-877 Simplify register_ironic_node

register_ironic_node was our worst offender in the new cyclomatic
complexity check. This change splits that function up into smaller,
simpler methods that each operate at a single level of abstraction.

Upstream-ref: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/131999
Change-Id: I57537c42898fc0cb5e155a69cb7734e55761aeff

commit_message:
Updating 'Entropy to Instances' section of the Security Guide

Formatted Entropy section and integrated Virtio RNG tool with current
EGD section, and including docbook formatting for files and literals.

commit_message:
CORE-877 Adds capabilities to Ironic nodes

If present in baremetal.json, the given capabilities will be added to
the nodes. This gives the ability to target particular nodes by creating
flavors which demand those capabilities.

Depends informally on I0855f6095704fe9da3cb337908957b500de542d7 which
adds capabilities to the baremetal.json file in the first place (but is
in a different repo).

Upstream-ref: None
Change-Id: I9d4eb625f3fd383dde18dd1ba4117c88e59c0305

commit_message:
Fix legacy alarm matching_metadata broken by recent fix.

The prefix was being computed incorrectly because meter_name is now
being stripped from kwargs. This patch computes the prefix before
kwargs is modified.

Change-Id: I858dd430a4ce4be5cda41b3dd7faa76b8fdf2cfe
Closes-Bug: #1383521

commit_message:
Speed up assign_ips and assign_admin_ips methods

assign_ips assign_admin_ips methods are the bottlenecks during deployment,
changes in this methods reduce execution time near 10 times

* added and correct tests
* added ignored_keys param to diff method to ignore some keys during
comparing two dictionaries, this is good when we are not sure or we are
not able to predict values in dictionary
* improved assign_ips and assign_admin_ips methods

Change-Id: I6b60ff722211ddb634c791fbb700a2e46c7143bc
Closes-Bug: #1384623
Blueprint: 100-nodes-support

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others

commit_message:
Add concrete example for stack creation and update.

Replaces the placeholder-based example with a concrete one. The
example creates a simple stack and prints a hello world message.
Some parameter might be required to change for the example to
be reproducible (i.e. the flavor). The update operation switches
the flavor used in the earlier stack.

Change-Id: I10a7ab1afb3dd55be8865abe9c2b66d0d27ce948

"}]
commit_message:
Adapt puppet module ntp for Fuel

Rename template name for ntp.
Strictly, in current implementation (v3.1.1), ntp module not need for explicit declare config_template var,
cause all logic from templates was moved to manifests (class ntp::params) and now it's only one template,
declared by default.
But since we don't want to change upstream modules and in declaration of 'openstack::clocksync'
config_template have default value as 'undef', so we need to save declare of this value at our module.

Change-Id: I8f9ac3bdacbd5512224bb4b1a5b9214bed54093c
Implements: blueprint merge-openstack-puppet-modules

I tested this today and it works for me. All functional tests passed, and the code itself looks good to me.

The question is how to use this? I think there are two possibilities:

1. Use 3 (or whatever you like) replicas in Swift and let Swift take care of the replication. In that case Ceph would not need to take care of that.
2. Use Swift with a single copy and let Ceph take care of replication. I'm not sure about this? See my comment on quarantining objects, this might cause trouble then.

I would like to do some more stress tests, ie. running ssbench against a couple of nodes."}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-03-07 18:27:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Since ceph is already doing it's own durability, it seems weird to layer the complexity of both systems and also do double replication. It seems to make more sense to me to have Swift do the durability across ceph volumes (and don't do it inside of ceph), but then get ceph to use Swift's /endpoints API (or something similar) to provide some value-add features between block and object.

But I also struggle, conceptually, about layering Swift with other systems like this."}, {'account_id': 8298, 'date': '2014-03-09 14:54:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)

commit_message:
RADOS (CEPH) DiskFile Backend

With multi-backend feature, SWIFT diskfile
can be backed by several object stores.

This commit adds RADOS (the object store of CEPH)
backend to the multi-backend feature of SWIFT.

blueprint implement-ceph-rados-as-a-backend-for-swift-multibackend

Change-Id: I13c44b2c715de12feab82534bb6cc4f4f066f0c4

commit_message:
Adapt synced swift module

- Moved device_dirs out of swift module to openstack::storage_node
- Removed some unused parameters
- 'ring_devices' type moved to 'osnailyfacter' module
- Moved log settings from hardcoded templates to class params
  Upstream Change-Id: I173652ec5bbe8d4382e10db4510d91aebceacab5
- Moved swift::notify::ceilometer to 'openstack' module
- Included fix for upstream bug #1384149
  Upstream Change-Id: I97da480fcf5ce62da99c31481b181b8b61375db5

Implements: blueprint merge-openstack-puppet-modules

Change-Id: I36ca6d4e1215a0b788d08d2f2a4c25c8ab851bf2

commit_message:
Remove warning & change @periodic_task behaviour

During development of Juno, Ia227f4c4e69ecf361ab02d1d17a3010303650104
added a warning that the behaviour of periodic_tasks with an interval of
0 would change.  This patch changes the behaviour and removes the
warning.

Oslo (which provides the @periodic_task decorator) uses spacing=0 to
mean "run at the default interval of 60s", but several nova methods used
spacing=0 to mean "don't run".  These methods now behave consistently
with the Oslo code.

Due to an error in the original patch, some of the warnings refer to the
intended behaviour change as being in "the K release", and some to "Juno".
The warning about changing behaviour is first present in Juno, so this
patch should be merged in Kilo.

Change-Id: Ie5f2092a3b84e3674fe6a68ce511d2dc218bb625
Closes-bug: 1276203

commit_message:
Fix disk matching issue in fuel-agent

Disk matching to be failed if devices have the same 'by-path' links.
With this change disk matching will work fine even on VirtualBox
environment (the latter known as having that issue with links).

Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning
Change-Id: I511c9756f54acee7d600c3f96372830f8803cbfb

Remove 'set -x' from run_tests.sh

Removed because it makes --help hard to read.
Also it's hard to figure out what happened and
where was the error.

commit_message:
Sync Tempest plugin with latest Tempest changes

Tempest project uses tempest_lib after commit merge:

https://github.com/openstack/tempest/commit/411130a0

Hence we need to update our plugin to be compatible with it.

Change-Id: I9ac0a7be8e942c83759e08cc1d16f332c08960ff

commit_message:
Use keystonemiddleware package

keystonemiddleware package will be used instead of deprecated
keystoneclient.middleware module to authorize requests with
keystone auth_token
python-keystoneclient was left as a requirement to allow
usage of 'keystone' command and updated to new version

Change-Id: I525a4914dba31f7f0309900936ace01f9752866d
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments
Related-Bug: #1383616
Depends: I90005ac4054cc585fd23c0e91cfcd51ef1ce6a9d

commit_message:
Add python-keystonemiddleware package to nailgun

Nailgun now requires keystonemiddleware package to use it
instead of outdated keystoneclient.middleware
Leave python-keystoneclient requirement as it is useful but
upgrade it to new version

Change-Id: I90005ac4054cc585fd23c0e91cfcd51ef1ce6a9d
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments
Related-Bug: #1383616

commit_message:
Use keystonemiddleware package

keystonemiddleware package will be used instead of deprecated
keystoneclient.middleware module to authorize requests with
keystone auth_token

Update python-keystoneclient to match version in our repos

Change-Id: Ib6025a5d243c76995ca1efac16d5d5025241f81c
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments
Related-Bug: #1383616
Depends: I32848ccd2279c1467818e1ff9e1a19becc9f7ae7

commit_message:
Ask for password during upgrade

Upgrades will no longer use password stored in astute.yaml
Now there are two ways to pass admin password to upgrade script:
* new `--password` argument in CLI
* prompt for password when password was not specified by `--password`
When no password was provided error is raised.

Changed where logging is initialized to make CLI tests easier

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments

Change-Id: Icc0f952729517fb94ee90ab98b0ee313bc213330

commit_message:
Remove usage of admin_token

* Added new tenant/project: services
* Added two new users with admin roles to 'services' project:
  ostf and nailgun
* Use generated passwords for ostf and nailgun keystone users and
  remove admin_token
* OSTF and nailgun will use their users to validate keystone tokens
  instead of admin_token
* Added new services and endpoints for keystone, ostf, nailgun. Now
  it's possible to use keystone service catalog to discover their URLs

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments
Depends: Ibe3844da784656f02673c32c2f98cb67bbdb3e89

Change-Id: I9860257b1b392be31de8ff9e09b95e9a3c6ba3f7

commit_message:
Generate new keystone credentials during upgrade

We need to generate new users and their passwords during upgrade.
On fresh install it is created by fuelmenu.

Change-Id: Ibe3844da784656f02673c32c2f98cb67bbdb3e89
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments

commit_message:
Remove usage of admin_token in nailgun

Instead of using admin_token in nailgun to verify keystone
tokens, nailgun will have dedicated service user to do that.

Change-Id: I3cf8f43cb03bfe3c523d78f57d2082451187649b
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments

commit_message:
Add dianogstic_name and fail_on_error to serialized task

By default add diagnostic_name which is equals to:
plugin.name-plugin.version
And fail_on_error which can be provided by task input
equals to True

related to blueprint cinder-neutron-plugins-in-fuel

Change-Id: Iceb483f816fc84192bb0d669c3fb360843d0cd3a

commit_message:
Fix node stats and notifications refresh after logging in

Currently node stats and notifications are not polled if the user
was not logged in when UI is loaded.

Change-Id: Idfb5a3bed6753652c84c94918e0f806ba8146aca
Closes-Bug: #1387626

commit_message:
Optimize speed of deletion in find command

I would like to recommend to use + instead of \; in the find
command. As this will ensure the removal of all selected
directories in a single invocation.

Hence improve the speed of deletion.

Change-Id: I409fe11aae217afb6f790491591005c679264ed4

commit_message:
Modal forms have extra borders

When forms are launched in a modal dialog, they appear fine.
When launched into a new tab, they contain extra borders.
This patch removes the extra borders and small refactor.

Change-Id: I7bedb0e9496195e1201a538266f456bea4ba6160
Closes-Bug: #1386352

LGTM'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-14 09:16:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

>  what are we getting out of it, besides a cludgy validate?

Nothing, hence my initial comments - as mentioned in Qiming's response, I believe the long-term strategy is to decouple the AWS and native *Group resources, as atm we've got some already ugly coupling there, e.g the native ASG inherits from the AWS one.

I agree that abstracting into utility functions might be a cleaner way to go, particularly since the inheritance in this case seems basically broken given that there's hacks required to bypass the superclass implementation in both cases."}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2014-10-14 12:13:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

> I agree that abstracting into utility functions might be a cleaner way to go

Well, I see two extremes here: 1) break all inheritances here, each resource type is implemented independently; 2) strict OO design and implementation.  Neither one sounds the right solution, at least from a pragmatist's perspective.  I saw no obvious conflicts between the reorg of the class hierarchy and the abstraction of common code into utilities function/modules.

I am a little worried of the confusion caused by InstanceGroup not being a specialized ResourceGroup.  Telling users that ResourceGroup was an out-of-band implementation won't mean a thing to them.

> particularly since the inheritance in this case seems basically broken given that there's hacks required to bypass the superclass implementation in both cases.

This is caused by a design flaw in ResourceGroup, why the property is named 'resource_def'?  In InstanceGroup, the same role is implemented as LaunchConfiguration, then later on in Heat AutoScalingGroup, it is replaced by 'resource'. In ResourceGroup there is 'count', while in InstanceGroup, it is called 'size'...

I had been warned when I initiated this effort: there won't be immediate benefits and it is a lot of work.  Now I'm stuck here, confused...  Should I abandon this and start fixing quite some bugs found in Heat AutoScalingResourceGroup with caution that I am not introducing bugs in the AWS version?"}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2014-10-30 11:43:47.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

abandoned in favor of a flat class hierarchy'}]

This patch makes InstanceGroup a subclass of ResourceGroup, without
breaking existing test cases while introducing no new code that
necessitates new test cases.

The most important changes are:

 - Have ResourceGroup.validate() only do validation on its own
   properties (i.e. resource_def) without getting in the way of
   property validation for InstanceGroup.

 - Replace InstanceGroup._resolve_attributes() with FnGetAtt() so
   that the same method in ResourceGroup is overriden.

commit_message:
Make InstanceGroup subclass of ResourceGroup

This patch makes InstanceGroup a subclass of ResourceGroup, without
breaking existing test cases while introducing no new code that
necessitates new test cases.

The most important changes are:

 - Have ResourceGroup.validate() only do validation on its own
   properties (i.e. resource_def) without getting in the way of
   property validation for InstanceGroup.

 - Add InstanceGroup.FnGetAtt() method that directly invokes the
   Resource.FnGetAtt() so that the same method in ResourceGroup is
   bypassed.

Change-Id: Ie0db5e891c12dedffa3cfa74613f593436d91e9e
Implements: partial-blueprint reorg-asg-code

commit_message:
Unset trap before dracut ramdisk build script exits

A similar change was needed in the normal ramdisk element as part
of ae928057bd2fc2205c91bf052d5503de64f9ea69 to avoid running
cleanup immediately after the ramdisk build completes.

Change-Id: Ia96e2d8011b88ed96cc6727914c5a5d2dea59757

Add __repr__ method for sample.Sample

sample.Sample has no string format method, which will cause useless
message when print log.

Change-Id: I8b9863a4ac6ee3373e18d36681fbfc4c89732111
Closes-Bug: #1386187

Figured out which two tests were failing and fixed them:

Used mox to mock sys.exc_info(). When an exception was raised for an UnexpectedMethodCallError by mox, the exception comparison code was subjected to the mock and caused testtools for Jenkins to go BOOM, report success for the offending tests, and bail on rest of tests for workers that ran failing tests. Also, it gave no info on the tests that failed. I figured out which tests were causing the problem by comparing the number of tests ran per worker and looking at the last test ran for the two workers that hadn't run their fair share of the total tests. Using pdb, I was able to see what was going on even though the tests reported successful."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 19:56:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Verified-1

'}, {'created': '2014-10-15 21:21:22.000000000', 'message': 'update retryable errors & instance fault on retry

HTTP errors can be split into a few categories: client ephemeral, server
ephemeral, server permanent, and globally permanent. You could argue
there is even more permutations. However, for simplicity, these errors
can be viewed as ephemeral and permanent. There could be some debate
about how these should be split, but a reasonable categorization
follows:

Ephemeral
408 REQUEST_TIMEOUT
500 INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR
502 BAD_GATEWAY
503 SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE
504 GATEWAY_TIMEOUT
507 INSUFFICIENT_STORAGE

Permanent
400 BAD_REQUEST
401 UNAUTHORIZED
402 PAYMENT_REQUIRED
403 FORBIDDEN
404 NOT_FOUND
405 METHOD_NOT_ALLOWED
406 NOT_ACCEPTABLE
407 PROXY_AUTHENTICATION_REQUIRED
409 CONFLICT
410 GONE
411 LENGTH_REQUIRED
412 PRECONDITION_FAILED
413 REQUEST_ENTITY_TOO_LARGE
414 REQUEST_URI_TOO_LONG
415 UNSUPPORTED_MEDIA_TYPE
416 REQUESTED_RANGE_NOT_SATISFIABLE
417 EXPECTATION_FAILED
422 UNPROCESSABLE_ENTITY
423 LOCKED
424 FAILED_DEPENDENCY
426 UPGRADE_REQUIRED
501 NOT_IMPLEMENTED
505 HTTP_VERSION_NOT_SUPPORTED
510 NOT_EXTENDED

The Glance XenAPI plugin has been updated to raise a RetryableError for
non-permanent errors as defined above.

Additionally, an instance fault will be logged every time an error
occurs. This will serve as transaction history where every attempt is a
transaction on the state. If a INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR occurs, there is a
retry, then a CONFLICT, the history will be in the instance_faults.

Deployers should configure the num_retries relative to the number of
api_servers. Right now, servers are put in random order and then cycled.
Trying the same server multiple times could cause unnecessary load and
delays. However, trying multiple servers, is ideal when a single server
is behaving badly or cannot reach another server it needs to communicate
with to fulfill a request.

Example configurations
----------------------

Try the only server once:
number api_servers: 1
num_retries: 0

Try the only server 5 times (might not be the best idea):
number api_servers: 1
num_retries: 4

Try each server once:
number api_servers: 5
num_retries: 4

Try 5 servers:
number api_servers: 100
num_retries: 4

Try each server twice (might not be the best idea):
number api_servers: 5
num_retries: 9

Closes-Bug: 1380776

Change-Id: I267a5b524c3ff8a28edf1a2285b77bb09049773c

commit_message:
update retryable errors & instance fault on retry

HTTP errors can be split into a few categories: client ephemeral, server
ephemeral, server permanent, and globally permanent. You could argue
there is even more permutations. However, for simplicity, these errors
can be viewed as ephemeral and permanent.

The Glance XenAPI plugin has been updated to raise a RetryableError for
ephemeral and unexpected (i.e. errors that are categorized as neither
permanent or ephemeral) errors.

Additionally, an instance fault will be logged every time an error
occurs. This will serve as transaction history where every attempt is a
transaction on the state. If an ephemeral error occurs, there is a
retry, then a permanent error, the history of each error will be in the
instance_faults.

Deployers should configure the num_retries relative to the number of
api_servers. Right now, servers are put in random order and then cycled.
Trying the same server multiple times could cause unnecessary load and
delays. However, trying multiple servers, is ideal when a single server
is behaving badly or cannot reach another server it needs to communicate
with to fulfill a request.

Closes-Bug: 1380776

Change-Id: I267a5b524c3ff8a28edf1a2285b77bb09049773c

commit_message:
Use wsgi.response for v2.1 unrescue API

According to the comment on v2.1 unrescue API, v2 unrescue API seems
to return a HTTP200 response on success case. However that is invalid
and it returns a HTTP202 response like the following:

 $ curl -i 'http://nova-api/v2/{tenant-id}/servers/{server-id}/action'
   -X POST -H "Accept: application/json" [..] -d '{"unrescue": null}'
 [..]
 RESP: [202] CaseInsensitiveDict({'date': 'Tue, 21 Oct 2014 02:23:42 GMT',
   'content-length': '0', 'content-type': 'text/html; charset=UTF-8',
   'x-compute-request-id': 'req-642b49e8-0e13-4923-a49b-6c8b317b7b8c'})
 RESP BODY: null

This patch removes the comment and makes the API use wsgi.response for
the code cleanup.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ie78e56fafd71f58568a0562b9a452f14d3b19815

commit_message:
Add pcre devel package for Horizon

pyScss python module uses pcre if available for performance
and it is better to be installed.
This commit adds it for files/{apts,rpms}/horizon.

Change-Id: If711fa222d3f395efd670334c8a84f35d195dc25

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-28 13:35:35.000000000', 'message': 'remove use of lockutils in tests

it looks like we may not need lockutils in the test path any more, so
remove it. This will make converting to oslo.concurrency a little
easier.

Change-Id: I56229e93ad61ac823646a4119a035d36c3400173
'}, {'created': '2014-10-28 14:25:19.000000000', 'message': "remove use of explicit lockutils invocation in tests

Instead of passing lockutils loading explicitly in the test run
command line, add the setting up of lock_path in the base test
case. This supports the need that lockutils are used in a lot of our
base code and lockutils can't function without lock_path being set.

It will not let lockutils be used for making tests run exclusively of
each other, but we don't need that today, and don't want tests that
are unclean in that way anyway.

Change-Id: I56229e93ad61ac823646a4119a035d36c3400173
"}, {'created': '2014-10-29 13:56:47.000000000', 'message': 'remove use of explicit lockutils invocation in tests

Instead of passing lockutils loading explicitly in the test run
command line, provide the support for individual test classes to ask
that lock_path is setup with the REQUIRES_LOCKING = True class
parameter.

Augment all classes that currently fail without this with
REQUIRES_LOCKING = True. Hopefully many of those can be individually
removed in the future so we can get out of needing external locking in
any of our unit tests.

Change-Id: I56229e93ad61ac823646a4119a035d36c3400173
'}, {'created': '2014-10-29 14:16:32.000000000', 'message': 'remove use of explicit lockutils invocation in tests

Instead of passing lockutils loading explicitly in the test run
command line, provide the support for individual test classes to ask
that lock_path is setup with the REQUIRES_LOCKING = True class

commit_message:
remove use of explicit lockutils invocation in tests

Instead of passing lockutils loading explicitly in the test run
command line, provide the support for individual test classes to ask
that lock_path is setup with the REQUIRES_LOCKING = True class
parameter.

Augment all classes that currently fail without this with
REQUIRES_LOCKING = True. Hopefully many of those can be individually
removed in the future so we can get out of needing external locking in
any of our unit tests.

Change-Id: I56229e93ad61ac823646a4119a035d36c3400173

commit_message:
Removed hardcoded IDs from "port" test resources

Test resources are generated using certain helper methods to provide
key/value data. These methods hardcode ID fields which map to primary
key in the database. Subsequent creates on these resources force the
database to assign hardcoded primary keys, ignoring DB's internal
mechanisms. Though unlikely, this could lead to primary key conflicts.

This commit removes hardcoded IDs from port resources. It also removes
ID hardcode from some more node-related spots.

Change-Id: I89f77ff31d1e5f7c534912dddbc7ff8e9dd9a932
Partial-Bug: #1268589

commit_message:
Encode x-auth-token in http header

X-auth-token in http header is not encoded currently. Need to
encode it in order to ensure httplib call will not break.

Change-Id: Ic23fc427ebf31f7629cc3dfd251b0a51dce664a7
Closes-Bug: 1387327

Unless there is a specific functionality of the python script that is not carried out by this patch, it looks a lot simpler and easier to maintain.'}, {'account_id': 287, 'date': '2014-10-17 16:44:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I agree with Loic: better use a simple shell script for the time being and not touch the requirements until we have a clear view of whether to keep using Landslide or move to Sphynx Hyerogliph (as Doug Hellman suggested).'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2014-10-17 21:56:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Stefano, this patch has nothing to do with requirements. For building HTML, this patch the same dependencies as the Python script under review as change 126246.

I do agree that we should put the requirements patch (and maybe the landslide Python/bash scripts) on hold until we have figured out which toolchain works for us.'}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2014-10-19 12:05:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9041, 'date': '2014-10-20 03:20:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi All - just a quick apology.  I started working on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/129127/1 for the upcoming training, and I created this shell script to help me test.  

The irony here is that we're encouraged to take the pulse of a project during the training so that we don't duplicate existing efforts, and I didn't stop to do that before submitting this patch.  I'm sorry for the confusion.

Is there a mailing list thread, wiki page, or IRC archive I should read to get fully informed on our direction?"}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2014-10-20 13:14:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

We currently have two proposed patches for turning rst files into html presentations:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/129131/ (this patch)

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/126246/

I am glad to have both changesets under review, because it forces us to reconsider our approach to building and publishing our docs.

There are several issues involved that deserve a thorough discussion. For now, I am marking this patch WIP, too.'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-10-20 17:41:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Enable Swift's newer feature of container-sync

Newer version of container-sync feature is introduced in Swift ver. 1.12.0.

The spec:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/swift/overview_container_sync.html

Before this commit, Devstack does not configure any realm used in
container-sync, therefore this feature does not work.
To test this feature in CI system, moreover to show the sample
configuration of realms, Devstack now edits realms configuration file.

Change-Id: I9f1e3224403e08e725a989162729470357fe90b0
Closes-Bug: 1378646

commit_message:
Ignore DiskNotFound error on detaching volumes

When volume_api.terminate_connection RPC calls fail due to timeout,
detaching volume will be impossible because it is already detached but
still have the volume mapping entry. To make it detachable completely
by retrying volume detach, this patch make it ignore DiskNotFound error
while detaching volumes and go through removing the mapping.

Change-Id: I95077179160a2eb35436db2a5f7a5fbca64ec323
Closes-Bug: #1367964

commit_message:
Add SSL PKI properties for keystone

To implement the SSL PKI spec we need to change the keystone ssl cert
and cert key properties to be more generalizable. We also need to
support the old properties for backwards compatibility.

Change-Id: Icf46132230512a31b6dec3c07164c95b13dd8f73

Hi Sean,

Thanks a lot for trying it.
Did you run "sudo multipath -l" on the source node after live-migration?
Per my try, you should see something like this - faulty devices show up:

stack@ubuntu-server13:~/devstack$ sudo multipath -l
3600508e00000000051807f310fbe840a dm-2 LSI,Logical Volume
size=222G features='0' hwhandler='0' wp=rw
`-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=active
  `- 2:1:0:0    sdf 8:80  active undef running
3600601602ba034003b1b9d778f3ae411 dm-3 DGC,VRAID
size=1.0G features='1 queue_if_no_path' hwhandler='1 alua' wp=rw
|-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=enabled
| `- 15:0:0:164 sdj 8:144 failed undef running
`-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=enabled
  `- 14:0:0:164 sdh 8:112 failed undef running

If faulty devices accumulated, a lot of CPU will be consumed.

If you checked /dev/disk/by-path directory, you should see some garbage remain.

Thanks,
Jeegn'}, {'account_id': 7677, 'date': '2014-09-16 14:35:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-17 16:27:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-15 14:07:28.000000000', 'message': "Clean up iSCSI multipath devices in Post Live Migration

When a volume is attached to a VM in the source compute node through
multipath, the related files in /dev/disk/by-path/ are like this

stack@ubuntu-server12:~/devstack$ ls /dev/disk/by-path/*24
/dev/disk/by-path/ip-192.168.3.50:3260-iscsi-iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.a5-lun-24
/dev/disk/by-path/ip-192.168.4.51:3260-iscsi-iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.b4-lun-24

The information on its corresponding multipath device is like this
stack@ubuntu-server12:~/devstack$ sudo multipath -l 3600601602ba034
00921130967724e411
3600601602ba03400921130967724e411 dm-3 DGC,VRAID
size=1.0G features='1 queue_if_no_path' hwhandler='1 alua' wp=rw
|-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=active
| `- 19:0:0:24 sdl 8:176 active undef running
`-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=enabled
  `- 18:0:0:24 sdj 8:144 active undef running

But when the VM is migrated to the destination, the related information is
like the following example since we CANNOT guarantee that all nodes are able
to access the same iSCSI portals and the same target LUN number. And the
information is used to overwrite connection_info in the DB before the post
live migration logic is executed.

stack@ubuntu-server13:~/devstack$ ls /dev/disk/by-path/*24
/dev/disk/by-path/ip-192.168.3.51:3260-iscsi-iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.b5-lun-100
/dev/disk/by-path/ip-192.168.4.51:3260-iscsi-iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.b4-lun-100

stack@ubuntu-server13:~/devstack$ sudo multipath -l 3600601602ba034
00921130967724e411
3600601602ba03400921130967724e411 dm-3 DGC,VRAID
size=1.0G features='1 queue_if_no_path' hwhandler='1 alua' wp=rw
|-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=active
| `- 19:0:0:100 sdf 8:176 active undef running
`-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=enabled
  `- 18:0:0:100 sdg 8:144 active undef running

As a result, if post live migration in source side uses <IP>, <IQN> and
<TARGET LUN Number> to find the devices to clean up, it may use 192.168.3.51,
iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.fnm00124500890.a5 and 100.
However, the correct one should be 192.168.3.50, iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.a5 and 24.

Similar philosophy in (https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1327497) can be
used to fix it: Leverage the unchanged multipath_id to find correct devices
to delete.

Change-Id: I875293c3ade9423caa2b8afe9eca25a74606d262
Closes-Bug: #1357368

commit_message:
Clean up iSCSI multipath devices in Post Live Migration

When a volume is attached to a VM in the source compute node through
multipath, the related files in /dev/disk/by-path/ are like this

stack@ubuntu-server12:~/devstack$ ls /dev/disk/by-path/*24
/dev/disk/by-path/ip-192.168.3.50:3260-iscsi-iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.a5-lun-24
/dev/disk/by-path/ip-192.168.4.51:3260-iscsi-iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.b4-lun-24

The information on its corresponding multipath device is like this
stack@ubuntu-server12:~/devstack$ sudo multipath -l 3600601602ba034
00921130967724e411
3600601602ba03400921130967724e411 dm-3 DGC,VRAID
size=1.0G features='1 queue_if_no_path' hwhandler='1 alua' wp=rw
|-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=active
| `- 19:0:0:24 sdl 8:176 active undef running
`-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=enabled
  `- 18:0:0:24 sdj 8:144 active undef running

But when the VM is migrated to the destination, the related information is
like the following example since we CANNOT guarantee that all nodes are able
to access the same iSCSI portals and the same target LUN number. And the
information is used to overwrite connection_info in the DB before the post
live migration logic is executed.

stack@ubuntu-server13:~/devstack$ ls /dev/disk/by-path/*24
/dev/disk/by-path/ip-192.168.3.51:3260-iscsi-iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.b5-lun-100
/dev/disk/by-path/ip-192.168.4.51:3260-iscsi-iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.b4-lun-100

stack@ubuntu-server13:~/devstack$ sudo multipath -l 3600601602ba034
00921130967724e411
3600601602ba03400921130967724e411 dm-3 DGC,VRAID
size=1.0G features='1 queue_if_no_path' hwhandler='1 alua' wp=rw
|-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=active
| `- 19:0:0:100 sdf 8:176 active undef running
`-+- policy='round-robin 0' prio=-1 status=enabled
  `- 18:0:0:100 sdg 8:144 active undef running

As a result, if post live migration in source side uses <IP>, <IQN> and
<TARGET LUN Number> to find the devices to clean up, it may use 192.168.3.51,
iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.fnm00124500890.a5 and 100.
However, the correct one should be 192.168.3.50, iqn.1992-04.com.emc:cx.
fnm00124500890.a5 and 24.

Similar philosophy in (https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1327497) can be
used to fix it: Leverage the unchanged multipath_id to find correct devices
to delete.

Change-Id: I875293c3ade9423caa2b8afe9eca25a74606d262
Closes-Bug: #1357368

commit_message:
Add elements for Ceilometer alarm services

Adds Ceilometer alarm-evaluator and alarm-notifier services:
* element for alarm-evaluator
* element for alarm-notifier
* configuration options for alarm services

Change-Id: I223d24256dcd4e9515149bdbdb9d021b0ef4d00e

commit_message:
Fix hacking rule H305 imports not grouped correctly

The recommended group order is:

import stdlib_1
import stdlib_2

import third_party_lib_1
import third_party_lib_2

import project_lib_1

commit_message:
Change how SELinux policies are compiled

To take advantage of macros, the custom policies are now compiled
using make. To use macros, selinux-policy-devel needs to be
installed.

Change-Id: I803291c01af709f39edcbf2f366808443233d7b3

commit_message:
Update doc/source/conf.py

* Exclude test files from source code index
* Add an index to jump to sub indexes in source code index
* Ensure the order of source code index by using an array
  rather than a dict.

Change-Id: I5c28a3e29c9c0b0332732d3f598030a77536563a

commit_message:
Add ssl options for ceilometer rabbitmq connection

Adds overcloud configuration options for ceilometer rabbitmq ssl port and
connection config using a shared rabbitmq parameter.

Relies on: I7b7613cb60b9095ba5665c335c496fea4514391a

commit_message:
Clarifying missed importance of attrs in hot-spec

Following the discussion in commit
I27f3a732480a851fd2eceb83e5fcc850ee59bb73, description
of some attributes (such as type in Resources section or
value in Outputs section) gives unclear answer, which
attribute is required and which is optional.

Change-Id: Ie6e207e427a577d46acb731cee495834faecd90d
Partial-bug: #1386242

commit_message:
Big Switch: Fix SSL version on get_server_cert

The ssl.get_server_certificate method uses SSLv3 by default.
Support for SSLv3 was dropped on the backend controller in
response to the POODLE vulnerability. This patch fixes it
to use TLSv1 like the wrap_socket method.

Closes-Bug: #1384487
Change-Id: I9cb5f219d327d62168bef2d7dbee22534b2e454e

commit_message:
New Features in 6.0 section for Release Notes

Added features listed in the Roadmap
Features are grouped as included in the 6.0TP release
and under development for 6.0 GA.

I did not include the upstream merge of Puppet modules;
this seems more like a process improvement than a product
improvement but perhaps I misunderstand.

I removed the update/upgrade issues for Tech Preview

Change-Id: Ib1081e45f8e79015d0bd1c5742abf146e66c685f

commit_message:
Network resource plugins

The resource tracker loads resource extension plug-ins to allow it
to track new resource types. The network resource is a plugin that
allows the resource tracker to account for allocation of network
bandwidth to instances.

The plug-in expects the network bandwidth requirement of an
instance is recorded in its flavor's extra_specs.

Co-Authored-By: Andrea Rosa  <andrea.rosa@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Paul Murray  <pmurray@hp.com>
This is part of: blueprint network-bandwidth-entitlement

Change-Id: I7e19510961c5d32e197d0306488ce9023e6a3791

commit_message:
Nova Pagination Sorting Enhancements

Currently, the pagination support for Nova does not allow the caller to
specify the sort order and direction of the data set. This blueprint
enhances the pagination support for the /servers and /servers/detail
APIs so that multiple sort keys and sort directions can be supplied on
the request.

Previously-approved: juno
bp nova-pagination
APIImpact

Change-Id: Id6c5e88c1c475aeff623db063ed0a24486b67b85

commit_message:
Use binary-deps.d for dracut ramdisks

Instead of hard-coding a list of binaries to include in the dracut
ramdisk, use the existing binary-deps.d functionality to provide a
list.  This will allow other ramdisks (such as discovery) to add
the binaries they need.

Change-Id: Ib7ffa15e08db1cc45e93a8f2a5c01369772c93ff

commit_message:
Split out aggregate disk filter unit tests

The aggregate disk filter unit tests remained in test_host_filters.py,
and this patch moves them to the test_disk_filters.py file. This was the
last occurrence of aggregate database calls from test_host_filters.py.

Change-Id: Ic47c41474dce8bf3936910be5feee081445193de

commit_message:
Split out core filter unit tests

Break out the unit tests for core filters from test_host_filters.py
into its own file. In the process, we mock out the database calls for
getting aggregate information instead of creating database records.

Change-Id: I9c602b9832632ad84b4b0941c5254a283d278b69

subject: Split out IO Ops filter unit tests

commit_message:
Split out IO Ops filter unit tests

Break out the unit tests for IO Ops filters from test_host_filters.py
into its own file. In the process, we mock out the database calls for
getting aggregate information instead of creating database records.

Change-Id: I8395ba7c09ca5c85ecd94d2cc670f3cd0880a373

commit_message:
Update table for netapp_eseries_host_type

This change adds the new config option for the NetApp E-Series driver
that allows an admin to override the host type methodology used by the
iSCSI client that is attaching to LUNs exported as Cinder volumes.

Change-Id: I0dcab31a0940aaa5f3b1e369fece4687f89acc70

[{'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2014-10-27 18:06:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-10-27 19:01:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

As discussed in IRC:

  * that string is two codepoints forming a surrogate pair
  * UTF-8 doesn't need surrogate pairs; it's a UTF-16 thing
  * the correct encoding of that codepoint into UTF-8 is '\xf0\x9f\x8c\xb8'
  * thankfully, this is not Unicode normalization, because that would be a thousand times worse

http://www.unicode.org/faq/utf_bom.html#utf8-4 says that (paraphrasing) you can't put surrogate pairs into a UTF-8 string; the definition of UTF-8 doesn't allow for it.

What if, instead of or in addition to this, we rejected any object names with a surrogate character in them? That covers this case (I think) and also covers the case where there's only one surrogate, not a pair. The standard linked above says that an unpaired surrogate is an error, but Python 2 happily eats it:

    >>> '\xed\xa0\xbc'.decode("utf-8")
    u'\ud83c'

Allowing that feels like it'll bite us when someday Swift supports Python 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-27 20:52:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-10-27 18:06:44.000000000', 'message': "reject problematic object names

We had this problem:

    >> : x = '\xed\xa0\xbc\xed\xbc\xb8'
    >> : x == x.decode('utf-8').encode('utf-8')
    << : False

That str contains two utf-8 codepoints, which I guess python is normalizing
into one unicode character, which it then encodes as one utf-8 codepoint.
Like this:

    >> : u'\ud83c\udf38'
    << : u'\U0001f338'

I don't entirely understand that, but having a different byte representation
after round-tripping through unicode causes problems with replication and
listings.

This patch just rejects anything that doesn't re-encode to the same thing.
If someone smarter wants to do something different, please speak up.

Change-Id: I9ac48ac2693e4121be6585c6e4f5d0079e9bb3e4

commit_message:
reject problematic object names

We had this problem:

    >> : x = '\xed\xa0\xbc\xed\xbc\xb8'
    >> : x == x.decode('utf-8').encode('utf-8')
    << : False

That str contains two utf-8 codepoints, which I guess python is normalizing
into one unicode character, which it then encodes as one utf-8 codepoint.
Like this:

    >> : u'\ud83c\udf38'
    << : u'\U0001f338'

I don't entirely understand that, but having a different byte representation
after round-tripping through unicode causes problems with replication and
listings.

This patch just rejects anything that doesn't re-encode to the same thing.
If someone smarter wants to do something different, please speak up.

Change-Id: I9ac48ac2693e4121be6585c6e4f5d0079e9bb3e4

commit_message:
Floating-ip-bulk-delete deletes associated ip

Initially floating-ip-bulk-delete was deleting a floating ip
that was associated to an instance but this caused confusion
as the instance was still associated to that floating-ip.

Updated the code so that floating-ip-bulk-delete method
first disassociates the floating-ip from the instance
and then deletes it.
Closes-Bug: #1265447

Change-Id: If0b55aca4d8796f7d00884618773bc25fa38e65a

commit_message:
Update table for netapp_eseries_host_type

This change adds the new config option for the NetApp E-Series driver
that allows an admin to override the host type methodology used by the
iSCSI client that is attaching to LUNs exported as Cinder volumes.

Change-Id: I0dcab31a0940aaa5f3b1e369fece4687f89acc70

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1/v3 scheduler_hints extension

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
the whole Nova API.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I75e281b9fc571c556842a708b06573601024a5ca

commit_message:
Fix the unittest use wrong controller for SecurityGroups V2

V2.1 and V2 API are sharing some set of unittest. But the unittest
for SecurityGroups V2 use the wrong controller. This patch fixes this.

Change-Id: I03cc6f3e4c1985fd961378d819c032f7a7c3d8ba

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-30 03:27:53.000000000', 'message': 'Fix Swagger initialization

It used to assume if /var/lib/cloud existed, then it was running
in EC2 but that caused issues with ansible or trusty. Now it
always assumes it is not running in EC2

Change-Id: I7cb93ac2184ade9c40222050b07069144affc491
'}]
commit_message:
Fix Swagger initialization

It used to assume if /var/lib/cloud existed, then it was running
in EC2 but that caused issues with ansible or trusty. Now it
always assumes it is not running in EC2

Change-Id: I7cb93ac2184ade9c40222050b07069144affc491

Remove token persistence proxy

Remove the persistence backend proxy classes that were provided
for compatibility in the Juno release.

Change-Id: I5c4541136089bdf9e386ffdd859388e4b877188a
bp: removed-as-of-kilo

commit_message:
Support auth policy

Sahara need to support auth policy. This proposal is for adding
policy.json. The next step could be introducing Sahara-related roles.

Change-Id: If8705b4ab7834c4cd6b98cc106e35cd67c50d2b5
Blueprint: auth-policy

commit_message:
Sync with oslo-incubator

Remove deprecated gettextutils module.
Sync with oslo-incubator at commit
368daacaa3f4a65352f3e0c66a939a496c14ecca.

Adjust calls for modules that have moved:
cliutils.find_resource -> manilaclient.openstack.common.apiclient.utils

Closes-Bug: #1383179

Change-Id: I1f5750d0a5c3ed929b1c0cc13aa54bf05ee9bfb3

commit_message:
Use haproxy httpchk to detect a radosgw crash

TCP check by itself is only able to confirm that the Apache process is
still there and listening on port 6780, an HTTP GET request will get a
response code 500 when there is no radosgw process behind Apache, and
haproxy will mark such host as DOWN.

Change-Id: Iee8e02427d58befa51596867a5c4c623ee0ddbe8
Closes-Bug: #1385002

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

Hi, thank you for working on this.

This piece of HTML uses Bootstrap's Grid system, which you can read about here: http://getbootstrap.com/css/#grid

It would be much better to fix this issue by finding out what makes that grid system break here, and removing that, instead of piling up hacks on top of it."}, {'account_id': 11730, 'date': '2014-10-29 09:16:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2014-10-29 09:21:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Switch to using subunit-trace from tempest-lib

This commit removes the tempest copy of subunit-trace and uses the
entry-point from tempest-lib instead.

Partially implements bp tempest-library

Change-Id: Ic1aeddc2d0b217c41b6b9914ac3f269b80c4ec8e

commit_message:
Neutron metering does not check overlap ip range

Neutron does not return "MeteringLabelRuleOverlaps" error, when the
remote ip ranges in the meter label rules are overlapped.

Change-Id: I4c2536a7d38b5f6d311db365c8c108d5367705a7
Closes-bug: #1361264

'}, {'created': '2014-10-29 07:28:09.000000000', 'message': 'Add queue parameter for Target

'}]
commit_message:
Add queue parameter for Target

In current oslo.message amqp driver like qpid/rabbit, a queue name can
be passed into TopicConsumer, but in the oslo.messaging.Target, we can
not specify a Target's queue name for a notification listener. The
driver's TopicConsumer will just threat the queue name as the default
topic name. For a notification listener, if there are mutliple listeners
are listenning for the same default notifications topic that is
"notifications", then the default queue_name is "topic.priority" like
"notifications.info", "notification.warn"...multiple listeners are using
the same queue if they are using the same topic, the amqp broker will
just dispatch the matched routing message to only one consumer for the
same queue, then we can not see the other listener can consistently
recieved the notifications.

By configuring the "notification_topics" to add your consumer unique
topic name in notifier side, and for listener just only listener your
specific topic name in "notification_topics", that will work around this
issue, but we hit a problem that our listener is listeninging another
openstack based product, it's not possible for us to change the
configuration in such black box openstack. So we need to a fix from
listener side by supplying a explicitly queue_name for the listener
target.

Closes-Bug #1356226

Change-Id: I4c8b1159f1da7d076d852e32231ee84cfda17db9

commit_message:
Port SecurityGroupRules controller into v2.1

This patch port SecurityGroupRules controller into v2.1 security_groups extension.

This patch just move the v2 code into v2.1 and share the unittest. The other
v2.1 related fix and improvement will be addressed by subsequent patchset.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I23c6d7c70ec27068066e2a2e3c7764982bf8ed1d

Port security-group-default-rules extension into v2.1

This patch port security-group-default-rules into v2.1.

This patch just move the v2 code into v2.1 and share the unittest. The other
v2.1 related fix and improvement will be addressed by subsequent patchset.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1 "resize a server" API

Some v2.1 APIs(create/update/rebuild server) contains the API
extension feature, it searches extension methods with its method
name and operates them automatically.

It is necessary to change the API schemas also automatically based
on the API extension loading condition, because the API extensions
add API parameters.

This patch adds API schema extensions which are implemented with
the same mechanism (stevedore library) as the API extension for "resize
a server" extensions.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I3651da8c1d23ee1b5d4710b1b323ecf9337ca70d

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-30 02:09:28.000000000', 'message': "EC: Datapath - HTTP PUT handling

This patch is a first cut at adding erasure_coding type
policy support to the Swift proxy handler for HTTP PUT
requests.

Terminology:

 - object chunks: HTTP chunks received over wire
 - object segments: consecutive HTTP chunks buffered up to
   a min threshold they are erasure (en)coded
 - EC fragments: data and parity fragments generated when
   erasure coding transformation is applied to object segments
 - EC archive: concatenation of EC fragments
 - ec_ndata - number of EC data fragments
 - ec_nparity - number of EC parity fragments

Design notes and Assumptions:

 - Swift requires PyECLib for erasure code primitives
   (Hosted at bitbucket.org and pypi.org)

 - Rough flow of operations -

   - Proxy opens (ec_ndata + ec_nparity) backend requests to object servers
   - Proxy buffers HTTP chunks up-to a minimum segment size
     (defined as a constraint in swift.conf, 1MB to start with)
   - Proxy feeds the assembled segment to PyECLib's encode() to get
     ec_ndata + ec_nparity fragments
   - Proxy sends the (ec_ndata + ec_nparity) fragments to the object servers
     to be _appended_ to the previous set
   - Proxy then continues with the next set of HTTP chunks

   - Object servers store objects which are EC archives (their
     contents are the concatenation of erasure coded fragments)

   - Original object metadata (length, etag) is sent as part of a
     metadata footer

 - Assumptions around PyECLib -

   - PyECLib gurantees that data/parity fragments are the same size
     (with appropriate padding added)
   - PyECLib generates a unique header for each erasure code fragment it
     generates on encode() - the header has the fragment size
   - PyECLib store a digest with each erasure coded fragment for integrity
     checking
   - PyECLib provides a get_segment_info API to help calculate EC
     fragment archive

Changes:

 - Proxy HTTP PUT request handling changes
   - Intercept EC request based on policy type
   - Call into PyEClib to encode to client_chunk_size sized
     object chunks to generate (ec_ndata + ec_nparity) EC fragments.
   - Queue chunk EC fragments for writing to nodes
   - etags for individual fragment archives are tracked as they are
     sent down to object servers and compared against those sent up by
     respective object servers at the end of each PUT

 - Object metadata changes: object server treats fragments archives as
   normal objects

     Content-Length: Length of the EC Fragment archive
     Etag: md5sum of the EC Fragment archive
     X-Object-Sysmeta-Content-Length: Original object content length
     X-Object-Sysmeta-Etag: Original object etag
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-Fragarchive-Index: EC Fragment archive index
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-Fragment-Size: Individual Fragment Size
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-Segment-Size: Individual Fragment Size
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-TypeVer: EC backend type + version
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-K_M: EC number of data and parity fragments

 - Container metadata (Content-Length, Etag) still stores the length and
   md5sum of the original object

Under construction:

 - Unit test code

Change-Id: Ic588b340dd059956911ce5051f2abba1ad379dda
Implements: blueprint ec-proxy-work
"}]
commit_message:
EC: Datapath - HTTP PUT handling

This patch is a first cut at adding erasure_coding type
policy support to the Swift proxy handler for HTTP PUT
requests.

Terminology:

 - object chunks: HTTP chunks received over wire
 - object segments: consecutive HTTP chunks buffered up to
   a min threshold they are erasure (en)coded
 - EC fragments: data and parity fragments generated when
   erasure coding transformation is applied to object segments
 - EC archive: concatenation of EC fragments
 - ec_ndata - number of EC data fragments
 - ec_nparity - number of EC parity fragments

Design notes and Assumptions:

 - Swift requires PyECLib for erasure code primitives
   (Hosted at bitbucket.org and pypi.org)

 - Rough flow of operations -

   - Proxy opens (ec_ndata + ec_nparity) backend requests to object servers
   - Proxy buffers HTTP chunks up-to a minimum segment size
     (defined as a constraint in swift.conf, 1MB to start with)
   - Proxy feeds the assembled segment to PyECLib's encode() to get
     ec_ndata + ec_nparity fragments
   - Proxy sends the (ec_ndata + ec_nparity) fragments to the object servers
     to be _appended_ to the previous set
   - Proxy then continues with the next set of HTTP chunks

   - Object servers store objects which are EC archives (their
     contents are the concatenation of erasure coded fragments)

   - Original object metadata (length, etag) is sent as part of a
     metadata footer

 - Assumptions around PyECLib -

   - PyECLib gurantees that data/parity fragments are the same size
     (with appropriate padding added)
   - PyECLib generates a unique header for each erasure code fragment it
     generates on encode() - the header has the fragment size
   - PyECLib store a digest with each erasure coded fragment for integrity
     checking
   - PyECLib provides a get_segment_info API to help calculate EC
     fragment archive

Changes:

 - Proxy HTTP PUT request handling changes
   - Intercept EC request based on policy type
   - Call into PyEClib to encode to client_chunk_size sized
     object chunks to generate (ec_ndata + ec_nparity) EC fragments.
   - Queue chunk EC fragments for writing to nodes
   - etags for individual fragment archives are tracked as they are
     sent down to object servers and compared against those sent up by
     respective object servers at the end of each PUT

 - Object metadata changes: object server treats fragments archives as
   normal objects

     Content-Length: Length of the EC Fragment archive
     Etag: md5sum of the EC Fragment archive
     X-Object-Sysmeta-Content-Length: Original object content length
     X-Object-Sysmeta-Etag: Original object etag
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-Fragarchive-Index: EC Fragment archive index
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-Fragment-Size: Individual Fragment Size
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-Segment-Size: Individual Fragment Size
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-TypeVer: EC backend type + version
     X-Object-Sysmeta-EC-K_M: EC number of data and parity fragments

 - Container metadata (Content-Length, Etag) still stores the length and
   md5sum of the original object

Under construction:

 - Unit test code

Change-Id: Ic588b340dd059956911ce5051f2abba1ad379dda
Implements: blueprint ec-proxy-work

commit_message:
Set auth_version to v2.0

When no auth_version value is provided, it still should explicitly
set auth_version to v2.0 as the default value.
This is also to be consistent with other components. The current
code does not have 'auth_version = v2.0' in the configuration file.

Change-Id: Ie8c23ec2eef0b0ad70b4937e7ae68ac66188f1f2
Closes-Bug: #1387016

commit_message:
Change spec since v2 api is used as default

Since the cinder endpoint API version has been changed to v2 in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130738, the spec needs to be
adapted to this change accordingly.

This patch will break unit test unless the patch in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130738 is merged, because the API
version is changed in cookbook-openstack-common project.

I've run unit test in my local env successfully with these two
matched patches.

Change-Id: I28d182ff9e26fd31e5cd4f713dbffde3f04807dc
Closes-bug: #1385099

[{'created': '2014-10-23 17:16:38.000000000', 'message': "Allow create_user to be idempotent

Was updating the password all the time which would invalidate any of
the users existing tokens and might cause temp auth issues.

This change adds a token-get check to allow the password update to be
skipped if it's already current.

Broke down the provider CLI Environment into three categories (from two).
* Boot is using the bootstrap token
* Admin is using admin endpoint and admin creds, only used by EC2.
* User is using api endpoint and user creds, used for token-get.

The current provider design has the basic input parms (user_name,
user_password, tenant_name) and the ones needed only for implementation
all required.   I think the implementation ones should all be optional
as the provider can easily get them for itself.  On that thought, with
this change I started with allowing identity_endpoint to be optional.
It is used only for the create_user and create_ec2_credentials ascions.
I believe this is the right direction for this provider.

Having said all that, I also know that we have begun work on the client
cookbook to have providers for many OpenStack resouces like keystone
items. Since that is not far enough along yet, I decided to make the
changes in the currently used identity provider.

Added missing EC2 tests.
Added logging of the CLI Environment.

Change-Id: Iec2eb748e20389ceb70c25d8bfcfd078e6de67ad
Closes-Bug: #1383821
"}]
commit_message:
Allow create_user to be idempotent

Was updating the password all the time which would invalidate any of
the users existing tokens and might cause temp auth issues.

This change adds a token-get check to allow the password update to be
skipped if it's already current.

Broke down the provider CLI Environment into three categories (from two).
* Boot is using the bootstrap token
* Admin is using admin endpoint and admin creds, only used by EC2.
* User is using api endpoint and user creds, used for token-get.

The current provider design has the basic input parms (user_name,
user_password, tenant_name) and the ones needed only for implementation
all required.   I think the implementation ones should all be optional
as the provider can easily get them for itself.  On that thought, with
this change I started with allowing identity_endpoint to be optional.
It is used only for the create_user and create_ec2_credentials ascions.
I believe this is the right direction for this provider.

Having said all that, I also know that we have begun work on the client
cookbook to have providers for many OpenStack resouces like keystone
items. Since that is not far enough along yet, I decided to make the
changes in the currently used identity provider.

Added missing EC2 tests.
Added logging of the CLI Environment.

Change-Id: Iec2eb748e20389ceb70c25d8bfcfd078e6de67ad
Closes-Bug: #1383821

commit_message:
Adds IPv6 url validation support

Fixes an issue where url validation fails when attempting to
create an endpoint with an IPv6 address in the URL.

Change-Id: I179b0cb7e5546a3a051e5a1e6390385a833b9f96
Closes-Bug: 1386376

commit_message:
Split out num instances filter unit tests

Break out the unit tests for num instances filters from
test_host_filters.py into its own file. In the process, we mock out the
database calls for getting aggregate information instead of creating
database records.

Change-Id: I71516cee8b1660e8e8f76eae4ae831b34232289e

commit_message:
Remove outdated docstring for XenApi driver's options

XenAPI's driver options's help strings can explain how to
use these options, so remove these duplicated and outdated
docstring.

Change-Id: I3de257e75ba13352e9460070f5bb2a6d7cf36a4e

commit_message:
Migrate cli test framework to tempest-lib

This commit switches the cli tests to use tempest-lib. The code which
was migrated to tempest-lib is removed and all the existing test cases
are converted to use the framework provided by the library. Future
improvements to the cli testing framework should be made in
tempest-lib after this commit.

Partially implements bp tempest-library
Change-Id: If2c9b3895a30905bc3d62b8daef783878d78399a

commit_message:
Make allow_{resize|migrate}_to_same_host configurable

In preparation for supporting 2 node devstack jobs, where the first node
is an all in one and the second is a compute node. Make nova config
options allow_resize_to_same_host and allow_migrate_to_same_host
configurable so we can turn them off when we have two compute nodes.

Change-Id: If6989200b56c4597d6e8506d0dda2cc75d0881f1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-28 03:44:02.000000000', 'message': 'Fix expansion of variables in localrc

Use a trick of passing the incoming value through an eval'd "cat" run
to expand any variables within it, whilst retaining the quoting.  Idea
cribbed from an example in [1].

The movie "Inception" had less levels of nesting than this ini setting
stuff ... I'm about as sure of the reality of variables passing
between each level as the guy with his spinning top.  However,
test-cases are added.

[1] http://stackoverflow.com/a/20316582

Change-Id: I9fc99f3716cc53366907878adb00ae6cf3898f14
Closes-Bug:#1386413
'}, {'created': '2014-10-29 11:12:57.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Single quote iniset argument in merge_config_file"

This reverts commit e2c9fee8ed846aba124a2fc1bba245790ed7ba90.

We have decided that we don't want to support the json-style argument
as described by bug#1374118 (see thread at [1]).

This restores the old behavior of sending the argument in
double-quotes so environment variables get expanded.  As a bonus,
tests for this are added.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-October/049341.html

Change-Id: I9fc99f3716cc53366907878adb00ae6cf3898f14
Closes-Bug:#1386413
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Single quote iniset argument in merge_config_file"

This reverts commit e2c9fee8ed846aba124a2fc1bba245790ed7ba90.

We have decided that we don't want to support the json-style argument
as described by bug#1374118 (see thread at [1]).

This restores the old behavior of sending the argument in
double-quotes so environment variables get expanded.  As a bonus,
tests for this are added.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-October/049341.html

Change-Id: I9fc99f3716cc53366907878adb00ae6cf3898f14
Closes-Bug:#1386413

commit_message:
Fix up file-matching in bashate tox test

The current test does not match file files in /lib/* because the
-wholename command is missing the preceeding \*.  The whole command is
a little difficult to understand.

This re-lays the find command, using -prune to skip dot directories
and keeping a hopefully clearer flow of what is being matched.

Change-Id: Idd856e897ff97095fb116294a9187ff4b198fa26

commit_message:
Cisco N1kv: Remove vmnetwork delete REST call on last port delete

Remove the vm network delete call to the VSM on final port call and
ensure that vm network is deleted from the database when the port count
becomes 0.

Change-Id: I6c08a099adfce2fdba8eefec6aadeb68a780ac37
Closes-Bug: 1373547
(cherry picked from commit 4e1c4cbcd71833095534bea9ff7617c582c300d2)

commit_message:
Use common get_instance call in API plugins

Cleanup API to use common get_instance call which
automatically does exception handling. Not all cases
are handled in this patch as some require more
significant testcase rework and are done in future
patches to make it easier to review.

Change-Id: Id27350e6562636f81347b490db649744b6b41186

commit_message:
support OS_ENDPOINT_TYPE in nova client

This change makes the handling of the endpoint_type setting in the nova
client more consistent while keeping backwards compatibility. The
NOVA_ENDPOINT_TYPE environment variable is checked first, and if it is
not set then the more generic OS_ENDPOINT_TYPE variable is checked. A
--os-endpoint-type command line option was added as well.

Change-Id: I0d96f9f87106fc41a9853920f557ffad724859e7
Closes-Bug: 1382249

commit_message:
Support building wheels (PEP-427)

Universal is used to identify pure-Python module(by bdist_wheel). For
these, it is sufficient to build a wheel with _any_ Python ABI version
and publish that to PyPI (by whatever means).

Change-Id: Ib9fd0b4731406ca58a766f52c6e2680a5a4409af

commit_message:
remove ordereddict requirement

we don't support py26 in Kilo anymore. since OrderedDict is
supported in py27+, we can remove this dependency.

Change-Id: Iafe1cf4ab6de36f6be8ca84580b76cf2dc5b90a7

[{'created': '2014-09-13 18:19:19.000000000', 'message': 'High level interface

This is a roughed out high level interface.  This is a little
different from what Jamie proposed as he was initially looking
for something in the form:

    projs = conn.list_project()

And this is more like:

    projs = conn.identity.project_list()

I think we at least need a service namespace for the methods.
I also generally like the method names noun_verb rather than
verb_noun, but I expect resistance there.

Change-Id: Ie52986a9da84c8f3395757c08de7a01be30e0f2a

High level interface using the connection classes to access the
various services.  Only identity projects are implemented:

    projects = conn.identity.list_projects()

The service filter has a valid_versions added to it to map the
module name to the version component of the endpoint URL.  For
example, the v2.0 endpoint path is supported by the v2 SDK
network module:

https://region-a.geo-1.network.hpcloudsvc.com/v2.0/

is supported by the SDK module openstack.network.v2.

commit_message:
High level interface

High level interface using the connection classes to access the
various services.  Only identity projects and list_flavors in
compute are implemented:

    projects = conn.identity.list_projects()

The service filter has a valid_versions added to it to map the
module name to the version component of the endpoint URL.  For
example, the v2.0 endpoint path is supported by the v2 SDK
network module:

https://region-a.geo-1.network.hpcloudsvc.com/v2.0/

is supported by the SDK module openstack.network.v2.

Implements: blueprint highlevel-interface

Change-Id: Ie52986a9da84c8f3395757c08de7a01be30e0f2a

[{'created': '2014-10-29 17:18:15.000000000', 'message': "Update installation guide for Juno release

I updated the installation guide for Juno release packages as
follows:

1) Converted 'systemctl' commands to single lines.
2) Converted more sections to use 'systemctl' commands.
3) Added note about lengthy installation time for
   'openstack-selinux' package.
4) Explicitly configured UUID tokens and SQL driver in
   keystone. RDO needs to update or remove the 'dist'
   configuration files for services.
5) Explicitly configured local file system store options
   in [glance_store] section that appeared two days before
   official release. Although the Ubuntu and RDO packages
   appear to work by default, late changes to configuration
   files tend to cause problems at some point.
6) Explicitly configured authentication strategy to keystone
   in nova on controller and compute nodes. I think we should
   avoid relying on defaults for this option and reconsider
   for Kilo, particularly with RDO packages.
7) Explicitly installed 'sysfsutils' package on nova compute nodes
   because nova looks for it during cinder volume operations.
8) Removed explicit installation of 'ipset' package on neutron
   network and compute nodes because the Ubuntu and RDO packages
   install it as a dependency. Not sure about SUSE, so I left
   the explicit installation.
9) Changed cinder example devices from /dev/sdb to /dev/sdb1
   because LVM on CentOS didn't like the former.

Note: The configuration changes mostly apply to RDO packages on
CentOS, but given the time constraints, I fixed some other issues.
Also, this patch ignores the sahara chapter.

Closes-Bug: #1383925

Change-Id: I0c9bbbfe72b8f0358f00d4f82b90ce4976a90ea2
