commit_message:
Update installation guide for Juno release

I updated the installation guide for Juno release packages as
follows:

1) Converted 'systemctl' commands to single lines.
2) Converted more sections to use 'systemctl' commands.
3) Added note about lengthy installation time for
   'openstack-selinux' package.
4) Explicitly configured UUID tokens and SQL driver in
   keystone. RDO needs to update or remove the 'dist'
   configuration files for services.
5) Explicitly configured local file system store options
   in [glance_store] section that appeared two days before
   official release. Although the Ubuntu and RDO packages
   appear to work by default, late changes to configuration
   files tend to cause problems at some point.
6) Explicitly configured authentication strategy to keystone
   in nova on controller and compute nodes. I think we should
   avoid relying on defaults for this option and reconsider
   for Kilo, particularly with RDO packages.
7) Explicitly installed 'sysfsutils' package on nova compute nodes
   because nova looks for it during cinder volume operations.
8) Removed explicit installation of 'ipset' package on neutron
   network and compute nodes because the Ubuntu and RDO packages
   install it as a dependency. Not sure about SUSE, so I left
   the explicit installation.
9) Changed cinder example devices from /dev/sdb to /dev/sdb1
   because LVM on CentOS didn't like the former.

Note: The configuration changes mostly apply to RDO packages on
CentOS, but given the time constraints, I fixed some other issues.
Also, this patch ignores the sahara chapter.

Closes-Bug: #1383925

Change-Id: I0c9bbbfe72b8f0358f00d4f82b90ce4976a90ea2

commit_message:
The 'ignore_path' was updated to 'ignore-path' in 0.5

When 0.5 was released this option was normalize to match
the rest of the options (which don't use underscores), so
to ensure this continues operating correctly we need to
reflect that change here.

Other changes in 0.5 (not relevant but will list them here):

666805d Fix the 'ignore-path' config option
04a710c Allow overriding file encoding
5a43417 Add check D005 - no newline at end of file

Change-Id: Id1d1b0dc275fc17333d6bd4ef2aa24f114ff7872

They changed with the 0.8.1 release and are set to change again with the 0.9.0 release (https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/KAFKA/Kafka+0.9+Consumer+Rewrite+Design). A better approach would to be use something beside the simpleconsumer but stick with the kafka apis.'}, {'account_id': 12443, 'date': '2014-10-29 22:06:41.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

commit_message:
Switch to zookeeper for fetching consumer offsets

The kafka_consumer plugin was using KafkaClient's SimpleConsumer()
to fetch consumer offsets.  Unfortunately, each call would launch
one thread per consumer group, a thread which is never closed, causing
monasca-collector's thread count to quickly get out of hand.
Switching to KazooClient retrieves offsets through Zookeeper instead,
and cleanly closes its threads.

Change-Id: I4b1dcabf1fb204d5af5f538cea96f55a523ef919

commit_message:
Quantifying bandit test results

This change adds a score to each checked file based on the number
and type of issues bandit discovers. This is needed for automatic
test confirmation (tox tests comming soon).

commit_message:
Add RAM, Cores, and Volume Count to Quotas

nova has core & ram quotas. cinder has a quota for the # of
volumes. trove needs to support the ability to have equivalent
quotas, otherwise those who run shared infrastructure will have
issues like: the # of instances is below quota, but the # of
cores is not.

Change-Id: Ia6bf0a2003b692e4a0b35345be4a1deea2370e6c
Implements: blueprint quota-for-ram-cores-and-volume-count

commit_message:
Implement .bashateignore handling

Set up a list of files to ignore for processing similar (really similar!)
to .gitignore.  So similar in fact that lets just include .gitignore
in addition to .bashateignore.

pathspec doesn't handle the pattern matching correctly to mimic gitignore
but the actual building of the regex patterns was good enough to keep using.

Sample .bashateignore for DevStack:
/*
!exercises/
!extras.d/
!lib/
!tests/
!tools/
tools/ironic/templates/
tools/xen/files/
tools/xen/templates/
!*.sh
!*rc
*.cfg
*.py
README*

tools/ironic/scripts/
tools/xen/

TODO:

git_ignore_files() is a mash-up of pathspec's iter_tree() and match_files()
and once it is working cleanly we should propose it back upstream.

Change-Id: If0bc94e17cee20a8aeb09974bdda8f1a897239c2

commit_message:
Remove hidden directories from discover

Recursively walk to find .sh and other files from only non-hidden
directories. All hidden directories found in the walk are discarded
before doing the discover.

Change-Id: If7fbe0d667596e006efd2b1cc747149fd856e87e

commit_message:
VMware: fix compute node exception when no hosts in cluster

Commit 4033c0c9c16d2844b36fd5627717e7ce206887f6 casues the
regression. The result was a empty string and not None.
That is suds returns a Text object and not None.

Change-Id: I79e70e300f40eb3561cf56478d578f0f8cda273e
Closes-bug: #1383305

As well this patch includes restructurization in load plugins method.

Loading plugins....

Load plugins from modules:
	/home/boris/.rally/plugins/plugin.py
Failed to load plugins from modules:

Fix rally plugins

Fix the world removing extra plugin load in
rally.benchmark.__init__ module

Make logging more reasonable

Closes-bug: #1387192

commit_message:
fix the error log print in encryptor __init__.py

when attach an encrypted volume to vm, the error
log print is not right in encryptor __init__.py.
It will raise wrong exception info.

This change will fix the log print using correct
format.

Change-Id: Ibbe41e64ae6320efa53bdd97cdd5312457e65be7
Closes-bug: #1384531

commit_message:
Install additional oslo modules in guest image

We now have dependencies on code that has graduated from oslo-incubator
to their own oslo modules. We need to make sure these are installed
on the trove guest image.

Specifically we need to now install:
oslo.i18n>=1.0.0
oslo.serialization>=1.0.0
oslo.utils>=1.0.0
oslo.messaging>=1.4.0

Closes-bug: 1386342
Change-Id: I29b73acafc8c0b463fff9d4b95bae95a82c65734

commit_message:
Build guest-image with compat=0.10 on trusty

Trusty uses qemu-img 1.7 (Qemu 1.7.0+dfsg-3ubuntu2) which uses
compat 1.1 by default, which cannot be used on Precise. Fix this
by building guest images with compat=0.10 on trusty.

Closes-bug: 1386341
Change-Id: I20a577d479cdd1374e1befcf70af8b2ad16c6d0a

commit_message:
NetApp fix for controller preferred path

This patch optimizes the data path by choosing
the preferred path to access the volume by selecting
the controller owning the volume.

Closes-Bug: #1365881

Change-Id: I7069111dfd22d4fca92615b5730854f6d696ec13
(cherry picked from commit e6ea26ea1272f9407879b822b3913b4308e3f2f8)

'}, {'created': '2014-10-15 08:31:44.000000000', 'message': 'Check for concurrent port binding deletion before binding the port

When agent tries to update port binding (DVR or regular), the port
might have already been deleted via API call.
This is not an error condition but should be handled to avoid traces
in the logs

commit_message:
Check for concurrent port binding deletion before binding the port

When agent tries to update port binding (DVR or regular), the port
might have already been deleted via API call.
This is not an error condition but should be handled to avoid traces
in the logs.

Change-Id: Ie9436172151f0ecd5b3e4667328910b09f8ef141
Closes-Bug: #1370570

commit_message:
NetApp fix for default host type in eseries

This fixes the issue where the default host type
provided in mapping should be high performing LnxALUA
type for eseries. It also makes it configurable in case
users want to configure a different host type.

Closes-Bug: #1365884

Change-Id: I30992ca69c25c3c02334470aae90c32731a5f3f4
(cherry picked from commit a120ede9ae3f18756db07d1d6696b9ac773b84bf)

commit_message:
Invalid instance_snapshot causes KeyError

When creating a nova instance, if the instance_snapshot_id passed in is
invalid, a KeyError exception results.  This likely happens when another
window or perhaps a command line tool deletes the snapshot before the
page is posted back.  Memoize decorator fix fixes an error which masks
the error listed above, enabling better debugging.

Closes-Bug: 1386826
Change-Id: I195b4df84da3bd360b155db9ae733c34575ebe7e

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-28 17:13:01.000000000', 'message': "Avoid using lua locks

The default redis library will try to be smart about using
or not using lua based locks, it seems to not correctly predict
this correctly and then fails with errors such as:

''unknown command 'EVALSHA''

To avoid these types of issues and to support more redis versions
that exist in the wild just avoid using the lua based locks in
general.

Upstream issue filed:

https://github.com/andymccurdy/redis-py/issues/550

Change-Id: Icb01607efbe967c97e5da96bf40317aaf5857b14
"}, {'created': '2014-10-28 17:20:28.000000000', 'message': "Avoid using lua locks

The default redis library will try to be smart about using
or not using lua based locks, it seems to not correctly predict
this correctly and then fails with errors such as:

''unknown command 'EVALSHA''

To avoid these types of issues and to support more redis versions
that exist in the wild just avoid using the lua based locks in
general.

Upstream issue filed:

https://github.com/andymccurdy/redis-py/issues/550

Change-Id: Icb01607efbe967c97e5da96bf40317aaf5857b14
"}]
commit_message:
Avoid using lua locks

The default redis library will try to be smart about using
or not using lua based locks, it seems to not correctly predict
this correctly and then fails with errors such as:

''unknown command 'EVALSHA''

To avoid these types of issues and to support more redis versions
that exist in the wild just avoid using the lua based locks in
general.

Upstream issue filed:

https://github.com/andymccurdy/redis-py/issues/550

Change-Id: Icb01607efbe967c97e5da96bf40317aaf5857b14

commit_message:
add context to keystonemiddleware

this pulls in context module from oslo as it's required for
notifications (which will be used in the audit middleware).

syncs context file to: Id66aba0c600896521a4a236e0a97859735419357

Implements: blueprint audit-middleware
Change-Id: Id983775129dcc795ab91d37d3ba7d90cc6f6a7a9

commit_message:
allow for soft updating of global-requirements

This creates a devstack REQUIREMENTS_MODE which is how we handle
syncing of global requirements. The default is 'strict', which is
current behavior. There is a new 'soft' mode which does a
--soft-update for projects *not* found in projects.txt, which lets
them specify additional requirements.

Change-Id: I4aa606514131b5dde67d87f5c8db5a3f3e50fc03
Depends-On: I1f195ef9ff1509659848e14ec9936ff6f66a6496

commit_message:
Add plugin sub-folder and augment crypto plugin doc

This CR creates a folder for plugins, to make way for documents pages
for each of the plugin types used in Barbican. The existing crypto
plugin page is moved to this new structure and revamped to add more
information on how Barbican core works with the plugin. The new plugin
section's index page has generic information on plugins (extracted
from the original plugin.rst) as well as defining what Barbican 'core'
is and how it interacts with plugins. Dependent CRs to add content
for the other plugin types will be coming soon.

Change-Id: Ia63c4e46cc7f01c334b41ec22ce8e9373b1a79da

commit_message:
Remove workaround for Ubuntu Cloud archive

An updated version of software-properties with support for the
Juno section of the Ubuntu Cloud archive has been released to
trusty-updates.

The manual setup instructions can be safely removed and replaced
with add-apt-repository.

Change-Id: Ibc526bc790947c60544da6d692993afd5c501db1
Closes-Bug: 1362521

commit_message:
Set explisit mysql-wsrep package name for zabbix

So as there is trend to support wsrep mysql package only and
seems that normal package works not so good, so I set wsrep
install for zabbix explicitly.

Change-Id: I87e62a34d7cbc572cc1f9ec6baded1404c76f0e3
Closes-Bug: #1368151

commit_message:
Also tie Haproxy_service to nova_floating_range waits

This commit makes all openstack::ha::haproxy_service
finish before we start checking for backends for
nova_floating_range.

Change-Id: I300c02290095ad1242524fb79c6d722941c1218f
Closes-bug: #1381982

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-16 19:50:44.000000000', 'message': "Make separate calls to libvirt volume

This is a follow up patch to
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116998/, where libvirt
volume's connect_volume method is split into get_config and
connect_volume. The following patch changes libvirt driver
to call the appropriate volume method, get_config or
connect_volume, instead of the old monolithic call to
connect_volume. connect_volume will no longer need to return
the libvirt xml after this switch over. This will improve
performance and eliminate possible race conditions.

Change-Id: I0d0d7ba98c53ad7509c28bb4866c488c0a049d2f
Closes-Bug: #1359617

commit_message:
Make separate calls to libvirt volume

This is a follow up patch to
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116998/, where libvirt
volume's connect_volume method were split into get_config and
connect_volume. The following patch changes libvirt driver
to call the appropriate volume method, get_config or
connect_volume, instead of the old monolithic call to
connect_volume. connect_volume will no longer need to return
the libvirt xml after this switch over. This will improve
performance and eliminate possible race conditions.

Change-Id: I0d0d7ba98c53ad7509c28bb4866c488c0a049d2f
Closes-Bug: #1359617

commit_message:
Split and fix the type filters unit tests

The unit test for TypeAffinityFilter was broken -- it was passing in the
instance_type['name'] key, when the filter class actually checks the
'id' key of the instance_type property of the filter_properties dict. :(

This corrects the tests, removes all DB accesses from both the type and
aggregate type affinity filter unit tests, and splits them out into
their own test file.

Change-Id: I5fc27c538cc419b4ed972839751e0e779151fc58

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Used schema to compute columns for datasource rows

Previously, the column names used to display rows for a datasource
were Col0, Col1, etc.

This change derives the column names from the schema exposed by
the datasource.

Change-Id: Ia541c2a5e6df4d6d7a41d6f2d16a27ee0f6b2669

commit_message:
Make run_tests.sh work with oslo.concurrency

Instead of making the module a runnable script, oslo.concurrency exposes
lockutils.py as a 'lockutils-wrapper' entry point. Use it as such in Nova
run_tests.sh

Change-Id: I988c839e13bb20a8a74eca4d13bc5f93dcda7967

commit_message:
Fixes to datasource schema API

Previously we required the ID field in the get_item call
of the schema_model method to be non-None, but the API framework
always provides an ID.

This change makes schema_model more forgiving and ignores
the ID field if it is provided.  It also fixes a bug in
error-reporting.

Change-Id: Ie7fb35d66d3a5c1566b82a876ca4f9d056cb1cbc

commit_message:
Update docs to reflect HOT version support.

This patch updates hot_spec.rst and functions.rst to reflect the changes
made to HOT version support.

Change-Id: I61f77ba30b59d5954201072f59b03cbd3d67debd
Closes-bug: #1386184

I don't think it's something we should backport. It introduces new configuration options, with values that are different from the hardcoded ones that it replaces (before: 180 retries with 1 sec interval, after: 60 retries with 3 sec interval). I think it's more an enhancement, not a bug fix, so it does not belong to stable/icehouse."}, {'account_id': 11805, 'date': '2014-10-23 16:31:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ihar, I'd argue that this is a bug fix.  Would you be more apt to +1 if the default values were the same as the hard-coded values?"}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-10-24 10:36:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Corey, I think we will be able to consider the patch for inclusion if it does not change default behaviour. So please resend the backport with default values modified to those used in Icehouse.

Once that's done, we'll collect feedback from stable maintainers on whether the patch can go in. I would vote 'yes' since it may help for some setups."}, {'account_id': 8213, 'date': '2014-10-24 10:44:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

From what I've read, stable branches does not allow incompatible config file changes, but this doesn't look like one to me, IMO. Functionally, it works (almost) the same (if the default values will be set to the values they try to replace: 180/1 instead of 60/3).

Also, it looks to me that it solves an issue, creating an instance and also requesting a large volume as well. Creating a large volume (128GB in the example), can take a while, so the instance can get into an ERROR state.

Regarding the default config values.. I'm torn. On one side, it would be best to be consistent with the values it tries to replace. On the other side, the commit merged on master with the current 60/3 values.."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-10-24 11:06:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Claudiu, we had similar cases when we modified default values in stable backports to retain the original behaviour but allow those interested in using a new option to explicitly opt-in it by modifying their neutron.conf.

F.e. that's how we backported caching mechanism for neutron metadata agent to stable branches, by disabling it in backport (while it was enabled in master)."}, {'account_id': 11805, 'date': '2014-10-24 11:52:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the input.  We'll submit a new patch shortly with the defaults set to 180/1."}, {'account_id': 11805, 'date': '2014-10-24 13:32:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 12659, 'date': '2014-10-24 13:49:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8213, 'date': '2014-10-24 13:49:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

Thanks Ihar for the information. :)

Values have been changed to 180/1, so functionally it stays the same, but now the values are configurable. Setting higher values will prevent booting instances in ERROR state just because it took too much time to create a large volume.

LGTM. :)'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-10-24 13:57:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-10-24 13:58:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

To fix this, max_retries/wait_between should be made configurable.

and replaces wait_between argument in the above method.

commit_message:
Make the block device mapping retries configurable

When booting instances passing in block-device and increasing the
volume size, instances can go in to error state if the volume takes
longer to create than the hard code value (max_tries(180)/wait_between(1))
set in nova/compute/manager.py

def _await_block_device_map_created(self,
                                    context,
                                    vol_id,
                                    max_tries=180,
                                    wait_between=1):

To fix this, max_retries/wait_between should be made configurable.
Looking through the different releases, Grizzly was 30, Havana was
60 , IceHouse is 180.

This change adds two configuration options:
a)  `block_device_allocate_retries` which can be set in nova.conf
by the user to configure the number of block device mapping retries.
It defaults to 180 and replaces the max_tries argument in the above method.
b) `block_device_allocate_retries_interval` which allows the user
to specify the time interval between consecutive retries. It defaults to 1
and replaces wait_between argument in the above method.

The cherry-picked patch has been amended to set the default configuration
options to the same values that were previously hard-coded:
  block_device_allocate_retries=180
  block_device_allocate_retries_interval=1

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1332382
Change-Id: I16e4cd1a572bc5c2cd91fc94be85e72f576a8c26
(cherry picked from commit 66721eb2c0f53fc4260b2f0aa9a3811da0f7ddbd)

Current test_create_flavor_using_string_ram specify " 1024 " as the
ram string value and the spaces are meaningless.
Current Nova API(v2.0) validation is loose and the API accepts this
value. However, new API(v2.1) will not allow this kind of value.
This patch removes these spaces from the test.

Change-Id: Ifaabcf04e2600bcec8043c981e320d47d8dc6379
'}]
commit_message:
Fix the flavor ram string value

Current test_create_flavor_using_string_ram specify " 1024 " as the
ram string value and the spaces are meaningless.
Current Nova API(v2.0) validation is loose and the API accepts this
value. However, new API(v2.1) will not allow this kind of value.
This patch removes these spaces from the test.

Change-Id: Ifaabcf04e2600bcec8043c981e320d47d8dc6379

commit_message:
Handle missing local collector directory

We currently explode if local collector is enabled with the data
directory missing. Changing this to a warning allows us to have this
turned on by default without greatly inconveniencing users.

Change-Id: I36364ba1a0706a5a2c820eadd526f2ba424ac665

commit_message:
Move rec.priority into rec.data

From V2 priority is stored in the data field of the record, this means that V1
code has errors when creating records that can lead to bad data at places.

This change moves the record's priority into the data instead of a sept.
column.

Change-Id: I8733f7767dcbe0263c2c54861ed892adf0251175

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-17 08:40:04.000000000', 'message': 'Race for l2pop when ports go up/down on same host

With l2pop enabled, race exists in delete_port_postcommit
when both create/update_port and delete_port deal with
different ports on the same host, where such ports are
either the first (or) last on same network for that host.
This race happens outside the DB locking zones in
the respective methods of ML2 plugin.

To fix this, we have moved determination of
fdb_entries back to delete_port_postcommit and removed
delete_port_precommit altogether from l2pop mechanism
driver.  In order to accomodate dvr interfaces, we
are storing and re-using the mechanism-driver context
which hold dvr-port-binding information while
invoking delete_port_postcommit.  We loop through
dvr interface bindings invoking delete_port_postcommit
similar to delete_port_precommit.

Closes-Bug: #1372438
Change-Id: If0502f57382441fdb4510c81a89794f57a38e696
(cherry picked from commit 3cd2163d5105faad389bee5175ef446f0bb90289)
'}]
commit_message:
Race for l2pop when ports go up/down on same host

With l2pop enabled, race exists in delete_port_postcommit
when both create/update_port and delete_port deal with
different ports on the same host, where such ports are
either the first (or) last on same network for that host.
This race happens outside the DB locking zones in
the respective methods of ML2 plugin.

To fix this, we have moved determination of
fdb_entries back to delete_port_postcommit and removed
delete_port_precommit altogether from l2pop mechanism
driver.  In order to accomodate dvr interfaces, we
are storing and re-using the mechanism-driver context
which hold dvr-port-binding information while
invoking delete_port_postcommit.  We loop through
dvr interface bindings invoking delete_port_postcommit
similar to delete_port_precommit.

Closes-Bug: #1372438
Change-Id: If0502f57382441fdb4510c81a89794f57a38e696

commit_message:
Use keystone sessions for v1 client

This removes the code for checking if the service catalog has a version part in
the url or not aka /v1 and removing it as it's handled by the underlying
ksclient code in sessions. It also removes old authentication code.

Change-Id: I04109a935d7d94518c7dab05122a64ef37190d44

commit_message:
Change the default api version for cinder endpoint

Since the cinder v1 api is deprecated, we should change the
default cinder endpoint to use v2 api.

Change-Id: I88bc0210ffec6d5a6afea17ed62e60c041f5fa57
Closes-bug: #1385099

commit_message:
OSSN-0039 Prevent POODLE attacks

Allow SSL protocol attribute, default to only TLS.

Change-Id: I61ecc68920ad72e49b68880f4b7977cd1a3c476b
Closes-Bug: #1384438

commit_message:
Make update metadata segments translatable

The terms "Other" and "Filter" in the update metadata template need to be
translatable.

Change-Id: Ied108d0bf1b2f139ecbb36bb79b44f26ac911db2
Closes-Bug: #1385485

commit_message:
Ensure password is set correctly on existing users

While reviewing this code it became obvious that password changes would
not be honored for existing users. This ensures that any user that
exists has their password set if one is passed in.

Change-Id: I356a0ef833041d31029e127415be1719cc1c4348

commit_message:
Migration from PostgreSQL to Elasticsearch

* migration status saved into Elasticsearch
* tox handled for migration
* JSON field added into migration
* reports tests moved into migration
* migration run script implemented
* manager for migration run implemented
* production wsgi application added for collector
* logging error in collector fixed
* installation struct model and table renamed

Change-Id: I001010a13f4798505b4d806728b3376da57c90fb
Blueprint: send-anon-usage

commit_message:
Create Subnet button should respect quotas

The create subnet button (visible for each network in the networks list and on
the detail page when looking at an individual network) should be disabled if
the quota for subnets is at capacity.

Tests have been added to check that when the quota is exceeded the buttons are
disabled.

Change-Id: I7bba89c2d89a39220900480f0091bdc6215505fe
Closes-bug: 1369779

> do you have any particular concerns?

My concern is to have a good understanding of what the problem is. Both bug report and commit message failed to do so.

> a recent change introduced bash dependency without any obvious reasons and broke my environment.

What is this change? We wouldn't want to break something else, would we?

> i don't know about other projects because i don't have a chance to run their UTs on my environment. they might have some valid reasons to use bash, eg. using bash-specific extensions. otherwise they should be switched to sh, IMO.

I am not advocating to get all projects to use one type of shell, but it sounds to me that a better approach might be to make this customizable based on the user's environment.

commit_message:
tox.ini: Avoid using bash where unnecessary

Switch to sh, which is hopefully more ubiquitously available than bash.

A recent change (commit 085a35d657cf0fa41a402f2af66c4beaa0f60db2)
introduced bash dependency for "tox -e pep8".  It broke my environment,
where bash is not available.  This change aims to restore it.
As far as I undestand, the change in question doesn't actually need
the specific shell dialect.  So switch to sh, which is expected to be
available for any POSIX-like systems, would improve the situation.

Closes-Bug: #1382327
Change-Id: Ie023d2265d9949a3e3721f03e865e4acfb460de2

commit_message:
kerberos client plugin

Enable kerberos when doing authentication.
It will reuse any existing kerberos token and use it if the server
uses WWW-Authenticate: Negotiate.
depends on to requests-kerberos

Co-Authored by: Adam Young <ayoung@redhat.com>
Co-Authored by: Jamie Lennox <jamielennox@redhat.com>

bp: kerberos-auth-plugin

commit_message:
Rename constant to a more appropriate name

The DB_MAX_RETRIES implies that a query will be
retried that many times. 'retry' means it happened
once before. In the current code, if DB_MAX_RETRIES
is set to 1, the query won't be retried at all.
If it's set to 0, the query won't even be run.

This constant should actually be called DB_MAX_ATTEMPTS
to indicate that the variable includes the first try.

Change-Id: I13f088ffa38c40db7fd297173e892b4ad5c7fadd

commit_message:
Make timezones translatable

Use timezone info in Babel to translate timezones.  Sort
timezones by offset.  Update format to:
    UTC -06:00: United States (Chicago) Time

Thanks amotoki for suggesting to use Babel to handle this!

Not updating environment_version in run_tests.sh because Babel isn't
a new requirement; it's just being made explicit.

Change-Id: I15d39b94d441e9e155870a0593d11e67e68f9bd9
Closes-Bug: #1333927

commit_message:
Basic structure of the freezer web ui integrated in horizon

This commit add to the repo the basic structure of the web ui
integrated with Horizon. There currently nothing under the Freezer
tab, this is only a base point to start to develop the Freezer
ui content.

Basic installation instructionr are available in the file
horizon_web_ui/README.rst

Change-Id: I6e1ef399c869494ec1c5c9dd52a6d9adfd9360c9
LAUNCHPAD: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/freezer/+spec/horizon-webui

commit_message:
Make labels in Network Topology translatable

Fix the button and object labels in the network topology pop ups to be
translatable and concatenation-free.  Use "None" as the not found value to be
consistent with the network ports detail screen.  This patch excludes
fixing the status values.

Partial-Bug: #1323599
Change-Id: Ia0c92842703109401d758d5ac3ccefab9ccf6971

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-16 19:15:08.000000000', 'message': 'Only resync DHCP for a particular network when their is a failure

The previous implementation will loop through and restart the dhcp
process for all active networks any time there is an exception calling
a dhcp driver function. This allows a tenant who can create an exception
to cause every dhcp process to restart. On systems with lots of networks
this can easily take longer than the default resync timeout leading to a
system that becomes unresponsive because of the load continually restarting
causes.

This patch restarts only dhcp processes related to the network on which
operations are failing.

Implements blueprint restart-dhcp-only-when-needed

commit_message:
Only resync DHCP for a particular network when their is a failure

The previous implementation will loop through and restart the dhcp
process for all active networks any time there is an exception calling
a dhcp driver function. This allows a tenant who can create an exception
to cause every dhcp process to restart. On systems with lots of networks
this can easily take longer than the default resync timeout leading to a
system that becomes unresponsive because of the load continually restarting
causes.

This patch restarts only dhcp processes related to the network on which
operations are failing. It should be noted that if there was some kind
of missed notification for a subnet update, the previous implementation
may have incidentally fixed it by restarting everything on the off
chance that something else caused an exception, but obviously relying
on that would be a bad idea as exceptions should be, well, exceptional.

Closes-bug: #1384402

Change-Id: I0b348a1657a7eb3a595f9bf6b217716a37ce38c6

commit_message:
Make status in instance details screen translatable

Use the same set of translations we have for status in the
instances table to make the status in the instance details
screen translatable.

Change-Id: I2430b9211e9f1aa2d067c74e577ba5905b261402
Closes-Bug: #1383916

commit_message:
Implement a DesignateObject Registry

This is intended to allow us to lookup Objects by their name, which
will allow for simple cross-object validation schema references.

Change-Id: I823279b93ac4755d76bf850d164c15a61b1e496d
Blueprint: validation-cleanup

commit_message:
Ensure qemu-kvm is running when deploying compute on KVM

qemu-kvm was not being started on ubuntu, which inserts
kvm kernel modules appropriately.
This behavior corrects a bug in qemu-kvm package on ubuntu
where it only loads kvm module after starting the qemu-kvm
service.
For CentOS, this functionality is provided in the script
/etc/sysconfig/modules/kvm.modules, and it is called just
to provide parity with Ubuntu, even though it does not
appear to be broken.

Change-Id: I05017f991593c79dbd6caa60683fd6061dd71626
Closes-Bug: #1383800

commit_message:
Fix random fails of test_clean_volumes_after_reset

Wait for deployment and reset task to finish to prevent situation
when not all task has been completed.
Also more reliable way of simulating disk change has been used.

Closes-Bug: #1387066

commit_message:
Improve HTML report

In this patch:
  * responsive behavior of task report is changed:
    now we have minimal width with scroll bars
    and scenarios list is always on left side
  * `bootstrap' framework css is removed - now its responsive grid
    is useless, so other styles were reimplemented
  * AngularJS, D3, NVD3 updated to recent versions
  * Current tab is now a part of URL hash
  * Expanding arrows are added on scenarios list
  * Table row with `total' values is highlighted and always last
  * Chart scope ends correctly on large count of iterations - e.g. if last
    value is 1200 and limit is 1000, then scope ends with 1200, not 1000
  * Fix: more accurate histograms calculation

Change-Id: Ie9ed98443a7f2163bc5fbf0d416b9bda8c5b3b6f

the commit message for a proposed spec if it proposes
changes to the Nova REST API

Change-Id: Iab6df6bc2ba2505df981a6ce31ba5fac9737ad70

yum non interactive

Adding -y to the yum command.

commit_message:
NSX: allow multiple networks with same vlan on different phy_net

Previously, the NSX plugin prevented one from creating multiple networks on
the same vlan even if they were being created on different physical_networks.
This patch corrects this issue and allows this to now occur.

Closes-bug: 1367034

Change-Id: I343449648304328dffdd5ba070491e05686ee22d
(cherry picked from commit 6d1f864531d169a54bc239561840176012629316)

commit_message:
Do not continue to load page if its resources are not loaded

Fixes bug with unusable interface after keystone token expiration

Proper global error handling implementation is needed

Closes-Bug: #1386640

Change-Id: Ia0bb982a6e46b0bce7e08d0d34dd749a11fac42f

commit_message:
Replaces always disabled context selection link

In the context selection dropdown, there is currently an always disabled
link to do more advanced filtering. The original intent was to open a
modal to do more advanced context selection. With the use of RBAC in a
previous bp, the Identity->Projects panel is always accessible. This
panel provides the entire project list for the user. We can just use
this to provide the larger project list to select from.

Change-Id: I0d6674e75785206f3be48c8bf004a29906bb6860

commit_message:
Remove use of unicode on exceptions

Casting exceptions to unicode using unicode() can interfere
with the proper translation of the exception message.  This
is especially true when lazy translation is enabled, since it
causes the exception message to be translated immediately using
the default locale.

This is the same problem caused by using str on exceptions,
which was fixed by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116054/

In addition to fixing these cases, this patch updates
hacking check N325, which checks for the use of str() on
exceptions, to also check for the use of unicode().

In order to make it clear which cases that cannot be caught
by the hacking check have been inspected, they have been
converted to using six.text_type() instead of unicode().

Closes-bug: #1380806
Change-Id: I87bb94fa76458e028beba28d092320057b53f70a

commit_message:
libvirt: introduce config to handle cells memory pages caps

Introduces a new config 'LibvirtConfigCapsNUMAPages' to
the driver libvirt which handles memory pages capabilities
of the host in the context of NUMA.

Work-item: Enhance libvirt driver to report available
           large pages per NUMA node in the host state data

Partial-Implement: blueprint virt-driver-large-pages
Change-Id: I902510c190a1b85d860f2579b01b52bb13f4d034

commit_message:
Promote ironic sideways grenade to voting

The job is currently voting in the places where it runs today.  This
ensures the existing jobs are named appropriately (removes -nv) and adds
it to the gate of the places its running in check.  It also adds it to nova
check/gate pipelines.  The job will only ever run against juno branches,
so it is removed from devstack-gate which does not have stable branches.

Change-Id: Ied48252487f72517a1e8361f90ef49ae8d454885

Thanks, Matt, for contributing this.  Can you tell me, will this correctly handle the case of the VLAN network manager in Nova networking?  This is the case where networks DO get assigned to tenants, and a non-admin user should see only networks assigned to his tenant.  I do not know enough about the testing framework here to understand (a) how the test discriminates on VLAN vs. Flat* network manager and (b) in the VLAN case knows whether there actually are any networks assigned to the tenant.

BTW, I think there is a little switcheroo in the commit message: it speaks of tenants being assigned to networks, but I think you meant to speak of networks being assigned to tenants.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-08-12 14:09:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add list-networks test for os-networks API

Adds a test to list networks for a non-admin tenant
using the compute os-networks API.

For Flat* network managers in nova, a tenant is not
assigned to a network so this tests that when listing
networks with a non-admin tenant, we get something back
since the underlying code in nova should pass 'allow_none'
to the DB API when listing the networks for Flat and
FlatDHCP network managers.

Change-Id: I5c50607279a8a385ebe96bf498e3e95079d6dec1
Related-Bug: #1327406

Add translation jobs for manila

The manila repo is setup for translations, transifex is configured as
well.

Setup the usual translation jobs for syncing translations and templates
between git and transifex.

From Bug#1271576:

"Bug Description

According to DynamoDB limits document [1] it is allowed to create tables and secondary indexes with a-z, A-Z, 0-9, '_' (underscore), '-' (dash), and '.' (dot) characters. Also names can be between 3 and 255 characters long.

[1] DynamoDB limits http://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/Limits.html

MagnetoDB log

2014-01-22 07:46:06.565 11572 ERROR magnetodb.storage.impl.cassandra_impl [-] Error executing query CREATE INDEX ilya_dynamo_geo_table1_geohash-index ON "default_tenant".'dynamo_geo_table1" ("user_geohash"):line 1:43 mismatched input '-' expecting K_ON"

This bug refers exclusively to the DynamoDB limits (and is tagged dynamodb-api), not to any Cassandra limitations, so I believe that my patch does close it.'}, {'account_id': 8601, 'date': '2014-10-02 14:53:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Maybe bug description is not written properly but it's problem it the next: DynamoDB is able to create table with '-' and '.' and size up to 255. but MagnetoDB isn't."}, {'account_id': 8601, 'date': '2014-10-02 14:56:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

In description is written that according DynamoDB limitation we should support all what is NOT limited. And problem is that we don't do this. The first bug which you have specified in commit message is connected to validation only ant it really fixed."}, {'account_id': 7553, 'date': '2014-10-02 14:58:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 7553, 'date': '2014-10-02 15:01:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

You're right, the included error message refers to the Cassandra limitation, but the description is misleading. I've updated the commit message to use "Related-Bug" instead of "Closes-Bug" for that issue. Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-02 15:56:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

OK, that is bringing bug #1271576 back into this, I guess the patch should try to address the combined limits imposed by the dynamoDB spec and the Cassandra implementation. A reasonable compromise is to limit names to alphanumeric+underscore characters, and enforce the length limits (3-255 for table and index names, 1-255 for attribute names).
This would resolve bugs #1298588, #1308528, #1271576, and #1298633.
I will upload a revised patch shortly.'}, {'account_id': 7553, 'date': '2014-10-07 19:50:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 7553, 'date': '2014-10-07 19:57:12.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 7553, 'date': '2014-10-07 19:59:46.000000000', 'content': 'Restored'}, {'account_id': 7553, 'date': '2014-10-07 19:59:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-07 20:54:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

Added a identifier encoding for table and keyspace names that are not supported directly by Cassandra, due to excessive length (over 48 characters) or invalid characters ('-' and '.'). An internal name composed by a human-readable prefix and a MD5 hash (for avoiding name collisions) gets generated and stored in the mapping table magnetodb.table_info. (2 comments)

@Rushi We actually run both APIs against the same backend at the same time. So I think we'd rather have these limitations matching as much as possible."}, {'account_id': 8491, 'date': '2014-10-10 08:13:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@Rushi, Nuno, pls see my thoughts about code duplication in tests inline'}, {'account_id': 8601, 'date': '2014-10-10 10:07:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7553, 'date': '2014-10-10 17:12:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

@Rushi: The _get_validation_identifier functionality will be tested as part of the unit tests for create_table, which I will extend further. As per Ilia's comments, I will leave the duplicate code in for now, as that's the way it was before, and refactor it in a separate change.

@Dmitriy: I think your iterative approach to generating a unique internal table name would complicate the process without many gains, and possibly run into race conditions because it wouldn't be atomic. The code I submitted produces a guaranteed-unique hash, and still maintains human readability by including a 13 character prefix extracted from the original table name. I think this is a reasonable compromise, especially since the mapping between original name and internal name can always be looked up in the table_info table."}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2014-10-10 17:39:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(1 comment)

Hi Nuno Santos, verbosity in tests is okay for me now, so I'm not -1'ing on that. But I still feel it is necessary to write a unit test to test the "unit" which is _get_valid_identifier. The method is nicely isolated in the code, and it would be great if it can be tested completely as a unit in this patch itself..'}, {'account_id': 8601, 'date': '2014-10-10 18:58:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Sure I agree that my approach is not good in case of table creation with the similar name, but I believe that it is not frequent case. Anyway, MD5 hash length is 32 characters (not 16) and md5 not guaranty uniqueness too, so I suggest to consider or my approach with will provide more clear table naming mapping in Cassandra for simple analyzing and debugging (In my opinion it is very important) but if other core guys think different, I suggest at list consider using uuid insted of MD5 hash, because collisions are possible'}, {'account_id': 7553, 'date': '2014-10-24 18:33:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-24 19:13:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified+1

commit_message:
Additional validation; UUIDs as internal table names

Restrict keyspace, index, table, and attribute names to valid characters,
and minimum and maximum lengths as per
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/Limits.html

Use UUIDs as internal table / column family names in Cassandra
implementation, to deal with different length limits and valid characters.

Closes-Bug: #1308528
Closes-Bug: #1271576
Closes-Bug: #1298588
Closes-Bug: #1298633

Implements blueprint cassandra-uuid-internal-names

Change-Id: I47ea3dd15c6bf4b4946f626734f4d6e45375a48b

RabbitMQ parameter.

commit_message:
Set explisit mysql-wsrep package name for zabbix

So as there is trend to support wsrep mysql package only and
seems that normal package works not so good, so I set wsrep
install for zabbix explicitly.

Closes-Bug: #1368151

Conflicts:
	deployment/puppet/osnailyfacter/manifests/cluster_ha.pp
	deployment/puppet/osnailyfacter/manifests/cluster_simple.pp

Change-Id: I22887a652dc467b5d1fa34ee49ffc33cfcfc67da

commit_message:
Remove automagic file finder

I think we've agreed to just let bashate take a list of files, and
leave the discovery up to the calling test-harness.

This removes the auto-discover component, and cleans up the
error-handling slightly.  It will print the usage if you leave off a
list of files to scan, and will give a sane error message if a file is
not found.

Change-Id: If9ad0855dfbd10f2a55c98b139f99167dc85a2aa

commit_message:
Use Discovery fixtures for auth token tests

These structures can be provided by keystoneclient Fixtures. The current
examples are actually incorrect as there are no links provided by the v2
discovery response.

Whilst at it we may as well use the built-in JSON handling of the
requests-mock library rather than encode it ourselves.

Change-Id: Icf227971458c92db0b0c77b5e3d08d1a9fec795e

commit_message:
Guard against `None` value of User.email attribute

If email was not specified during User creation (it's not required),
it will be `None`. It would be safer to guard against already existing
`None` values than to prevent creating new user with email == `None`.

Change-Id: Id81a94491918190ceae4b08cd3293250bb4ab194
Closes-Bug: #1383630

commit_message:
Increase rabbitmq timeout

This change increases the timeout waiting for rabbitmq from 3 to 60
seconds. I've observed some instances of it taking 20-30 seconds before,
so I think we need to be more generous here.

Change-Id: I908eb75790d8b90410ed1b3fa018aec9630633d3

[{'created': '2014-10-29 05:15:16.000000000', 'message': "Use full path to grub2-mkconfig

Current centos7 builds on hpcloud are failing calling grub2-mkconfig;
from the logs:

 + sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
 sudo: grub2-mkconfig: command not found

To be completely honest, I'm having a hard time explaining why this
works with rackspace images, but not hpcloud ones.  I can not
replicate this in my own setup, even using the same hpcloud images.
Possibly it's something to do with the nodepool host environment when
it starts the script on the remote host?  Without access to a failing
host I'm clutching at straws...

Change-Id: I9d9f759fac1a96cc785354ae5aa44398c908704d
"}]
commit_message:
Use full path to grub2-mkconfig

Current centos7 builds on hpcloud are failing calling grub2-mkconfig;
from the logs:

 + sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
 sudo: grub2-mkconfig: command not found

To be completely honest, I'm having a hard time explaining why this
works with rackspace images, but not hpcloud ones.  I can not
replicate this in my own setup, even using the same hpcloud images.
Possibly it's something to do with the nodepool host environment when
it starts the script on the remote host?  Without access to a failing
host I'm clutching at straws...

Change-Id: I9d9f759fac1a96cc785354ae5aa44398c908704d

commit_message:
Delete errored share servers with deletion of the last share

If deletion of share servers is enabled in manila
(delete_share_server_with_last_share=True), we still cannot delete
share server with 'ERROR' status when deleting last share of this server.
We get ManilaException 'Share server backend details missing.' in this case.

Allow deletion of errored share server when trying to delete share.

Add unit and tempest tests.

Closes-bug: #1323720

Change-Id: I8810b8cef287675242185853ee49ccc794026c9d

When a rule "create_network": "http://127.0.0.1:8080/ or rule:default"
is configured in policy.json, create network with default values reports
a "Circular reference detected" exception.
The reason is, for unspecified values, default value of
neutron.api.v2.attributes.ATTR_NOT_SPECIFIED (that is, object())
is assigned by Neutron.
This creates a problem when jsonutils.dumps() is executed on a JSON string
that contains object(), thus reporting the said exception.
The fix replaces object() into empty string value {} temporarily in the
dictionary only for the policy check.

commit_message:
Fixed a problem with neutron http policy check

When a rule "create_network": "http://127.0.0.1:8080/ or rule:default"
is configured in policy.json, create network with default values reports
a "Circular reference detected" exception.
The reason is, for unspecified values, default value of
neutron.api.v2.attributes.ATTR_NOT_SPECIFIED (that is, object())
is assigned by Neutron.
This creates a problem when jsonutils.dumps() is executed on a JSON
string that contains object(), thus reporting the said exception.
The fix replaces object() into empty string value {} in the
dictionary only for the policy check.

Closes-Bug: 1233707
Change-Id: I2c2510a05f968bfaa5a43b435b7c45f30ec246d0

commit_message:
Add vlan_ids parameter

  'vlan_ids' parameter was added to l23network puppet module. Added
  this parameter in nailgun accordingly.
  Created NeutronNetworkDeploymentSerializer60 for adding 'vlans_id'
  to the network scheme attributes.

Closes-Bug: 1305600

Change-Id: I5c1b68191c8b875f8f0ec52010f9e6cadf1f8700

commit_message:
replace deprecated libvirt_* options for rbd

All libvirt_* options for Nova were deprecated in Icehouse and removed
in Juno, this commit replaces the rbd related deprecated options with
corresponding options in the [libvirt] section of nova.conf.

Change-Id: If9670e6df8dccbbb659d48d59e6a60b5583d68ac
Partial-Bug: #1386735

I think this patch is a big step in the right direction for verifying that the various driver implementations are properly implemented (and don't break).

I've been thinking of running tests like these under a devstack VM in CI.  We should have CI run these functional tests on a devstack VM configured with each of the supported backend brokers.

I know devstack supports rabbitmq, and I've recently done work to get devstack working with qpidd (both legacy protocol and the new AMQP 1.0 driver).  I'm not sure about devstack support for zeromq, however.   Seems like this type of full driver coverage testing is doable."}, {'account_id': 8784, 'date': '2014-10-22 15:22:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Add driver independent functional tests

Add driver independent functional tests of the messaging API

The url used to select (and configure) the driver is specified as an
environment variable named TRANSPORT_URL.

Change-Id: I867001a15ffaca06ae831cfd0240ed3397bf6503

The compute node snapshot on controller allows us to go back to a known global state in the cluster build.

For testing the network node build, I have a script that restores the pre-network node cluster essentially doing this:

vboxmanage controlvm controller poweroff

sleep 1

vboxmanage snapshot controller restore '"openstack-compute_installed"'

vboxmanage startvm controller

vboxmanage controlvm compute poweroff

sleep 1

vboxmanage snapshot compute restore '"pre-installed"' (this snapshot should be renamed)

vboxmanage startvm compute

I find that useful.'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-10-08 10:44:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Pranav is correct: if you wait long enough after restoring the snapshot taken when the controller node is installed, the cluster will sync and work again. I still find the additional snapshots of the controller VM useful when I want to restore the cluster to the exact state it had when the cluster install was finished.

Others may find it useful, and it demonstrates how the recently added command options can be used, so I am leaving this a WIP for now.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 19:51:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
labs: take additional snapshots of controller node

Take a snapshot of the controller VM after installing the compute and
network nodes.

The configuration of compute and network nodes is largely saved in the
database running on the controller node, but until now these database
changes were not part of any snapshots. With this changeset, resetting
all nodes to the most recent snapshots restores a working cluster.

Change-Id: Ifd2ca144d176280bc6677a2e6381afb63a9feea3

commit_message:
Add versions to requests

Make the auth plugin work more like a regular plugin such that the
values returned from get_endpoint are version dependant and the requests
made to the session all have a version number.

For compatibility there is still no lookup of the correct versioned URL
it just appends the default.

Change-Id: I2a8258ebd584aa35a94369fe4673dfd5ee07715b

commit_message:
Use an adapter in IdentityServer

Now that we are using plugins we can use the adapter to set the default
values on requests rather than push it through _http_request.

Remove the session from the base class. The only reference to it we need
will be in the adapter and maintained by the IdentityServer.

Removed one test assertion. It only seems to test that a config value is
passed through the class and the final location for this is getting
nested deeper and deeper. If the identity_uri config value wasn't being
passed we would have a lot more test failures so I believe it's safe to
remove.

Change-Id: Id092e8f42f843dbfbc1c30589b50ba341ccf4aae

commit_message:
Use connection retrying from keystoneclient

Keystoneclient added retrying requests on connection errors in 0.11. We
should use this in preference to our own scheme.

This is not exactly the same as the existing code. The existing code
catches any non-HTTP exceptions and retries the request. This has been a
problem in the past for example with AttributeErrors and such being
retried that will never succeed.

This implementation that will only retry when you get an actual
connection error is more correct.

I also remove the NetworkError exception. This is only used internally
and it is easier to simply catch the connection exceptions where the
NetworkError used to be.

Change-Id: I6c3c971ea1964cfbf50519e8faf0a0c7dff47598

commit_message:
Copy static files for packaged installs

Packaged installs result in tuskar-ui compressed static files being
placed in /var/www/horizon/static/dashboard, alongside horizon static
files.  We need to copy them over to
/usr/share/openstack-dashboard/static/dashboard

Change-Id: I369cba710c01ee09584d6f3de1c9aa7195dfcb69

startup openvswitch. This should no longer be required

'}]
commit_message:
Remove hack to start openvswitch

Updates bin/init-neutron-ovs so that it no longer tries to
startup openvswitch. This should no longer be required
because the openvswitch element is automatically pulled
in via the os-net-config element dependency.

Change-Id: Ibed45fc077756a5da6cb78494c2cdd21cda52364

commit_message:
Modify rally commands deployment, task, and verify

Small modifications to the rally commands 'deployment', 'task', and
'verify'.
In deployment, rename the subcommand endpoint to show, and remove
the pprint and json output options in subcommand config in favor of
pretty-printed json output only.
In task, perform the same in subcommand results as in config.
In verify, perform the same in subcommand results as in config.

Change-Id: I9686abf5088782e68111638da10be72c0e1135fa

commit_message:
Short circuit init-neutron-ovs

If os-net-config data is detected we want to prevent this
script from doing anything because network models
are being passed in via heat (generated via Tuskar)

Change-Id: Ia67e70ef6355d50e2b41bbc9d1e2ba0269305515

commit_message:
Replace ensure-bridge w/ os-net-config.

This updates the init-neutron-ovs script so that it
dynamically writes out an os-net-config config file
and then runs os-net-config to perform the required
network configuration.

Change-Id: I5f51ecb5c64fc9c13eabc16b2b43b5dda1b38d65

commit_message:
Update install guide to install tftp

Our installation guide never mentioned the need to install the TFTP
server. This updates the PXE section instructions to correct that.

Change-Id: I2e0c43d377888520d274e36b3523aceca72013d6

In some cases negative values can be returned for resources currently
in use. When this occurs, the project overview page fails with an
error 500 due to an OverflowError, "cannot convert float infinity to

Closes-Bug: #1386687
'}]
commit_message:
Handle negative values in total*Used for Cinder absolute limits

In some cases negative values can be returned for resources currently
in use. When this occurs, the project overview page fails with an
error 500 due to an OverflowError, "cannot convert float infinity to
integer". Handle this case more gracefully.

Change-Id: Id1ad16eafdde906dc74bfafc7f72ea8d3bdcdc8f
Closes-Bug: #1386687

commit_message:
Split and fix availability zone filter unit tests

The availability zone filter unit tests were broken, but the problem
with them was being masked due to aggregate fixtures that were created
in tests that happened to be alphabetically ordered right before them.
This patch splits out these unit tests into their own file and mocks out
the appropriate call to nova.db.aggregate_metadata_get_by_host() instead
of relying on database records.

Change-Id: Ic692d3e7c77047ae6d901b955bc504fdc5e73738

commit_message:
Reorder operations in (l3_dvr) update floating ip

This review overrides update_floatingip (L3_NAT_dbonly_mixin)
in l3_dvr_db (L3_NAT_with_dvr_db_mixin) to reorder the garbage
collection to after the floating ip is updated and rpc called.
This was previously being called in the (already) overridden
_update_fip_assoc.

Since this call is moved, the _update_fip_assoc for l3_dvr_db
is exactly the same as l3_db and is thus removed completely.

This tidy up was created whilst looking at bug 1381617. The
intention was to mitigate the timing issues exposed by [1]
and discussed in the bug report. It seems the problem persists
with more discussion around 'properly fixing' this at [2].

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/102700/
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130414/4

Change-Id: I24cef57bf394ceeb931ff48fa67f18218c734b00

The Cisco "boxes" are all sending slow LACP updates, the Junipers are sending fast LACP. Will be good to have not hardcoded only one value.'}, {'account_id': 7468, 'date': '2014-09-29 18:04:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

this value don't hardcoded. 
If it need, you can specify lacp_active=NNN (or slow) in bond properties
but by default will be 'fast'"}, {'account_id': 7468, 'date': '2014-09-29 18:06:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

s/lacp_active/lacp_time/'}, {'account_id': 8935, 'date': '2014-09-29 19:23:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

According to the IEEE 802.3ad standard the default LACP periodic update is "Slow" (every 30 sec). Linux also has it as a default value (see [0]). I would prefer to leave "slow" as a default value for us too. Or explicitly document our non-standard decision in User guide and Reference architecture. 

[0] https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/networking/bonding.txt'}, {'account_id': 7468, 'date': '2014-09-29 20:31:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

OVS bonds don't works properly with default "true" value, and works well with non-default. What will better -- keep standarts or have well-working environment?'}, {'account_id': 8935, 'date': '2014-09-30 08:12:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

What is the problem with the default value? You mean a very slow time of a failure detection? If so, it's not a problem. It's a well known feature.

I propose to keep a default value "slow" in manifests, but override it to "fast" in Nailgun. And, of course, it should be documented as a part of our reference architecture.'}, {'account_id': 9387, 'date': '2014-10-29 07:14:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1367776/comments/7'}, {'account_id': 7468, 'date': '2014-10-29 07:29:44.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Set error state when unshelve an instance due to not found image

If shelve image created by shelve operation can not be found when
unshelve, nova should set the instance error state.

This patch add a new param show_deleted to glance api:
:param show_deleted: (Optional) show the image even the status of
                     image is deleted.

Change-Id: Ie4bc8dfec0922023dd1a4204a67acd77f7bb0498
Closes-Bug: 1371406

commit_message:
Change logic condition for swift usage choice

Fix logical mistake when we are choosing swift.
Otherwise, any non-vcenter installation will be
using swift, which is wrong

Change-Id: Iea846475343671b7768a5b081c182217395be2b3
Closes-bug: #1384978

commit_message:
Do not merge: Test v2.1 API on the gate

This patch switches "/v2" for v2.1 API, and v2 API tests of Tempest
works against v2.1 API on the gate.
Through these tests, we can know backwards incompatible changes from
v2.0 API and working items for v2.1 API development.

Change-Id: Ia7ef1dd190c49ca3c8ada63cb7ffed161a1fee9b

Remove unused compute_api in extend_status

There are unused compute_api variable in extend_status
extension, this patch remove them in both v2/v3(v2.1).

commit_message:
Use RPC instead of neutron client in metadata agent

RPC is a standard way of interacting between Neutron server and agents
Using neutron client is also  inefficient as it results in unneeded
keystone load and may become a bottleneck at scale

DocImpact
When upgrading, one should upgrade neutron server first,
then metadata agent. However there is a fallback in case
metadata agent fails to get info from server by rpc -
it will return to using neutron client.

Closes-Bug: #1092043

Change-Id: Ib75568643e6062543c0ff8cf80fba1b40b4fe82f

I like the idea, but ugh, what an ugly API this is.

If you look at the request headers on a PUT, there's a pattern that emerges:

 * the "etag" header contains the object's etag
 * the Content-Length header contains the length of the content (the object)
 * the Content-Type header contains the type of the content (the object)

And then:

 * the X-Copy-From-Account header contains an object name

That's just confusing IMO.

Also, now I can say things like this in my requests:

    COPY /v1/a1/c1/o1 HTTP/whatever
    Destination-Account: /a2/c2/o2
    Destination: /c3/o3

Which one wins, the old or the new? Or do I get a 400 response? I don't really care about the answer, but I do care that I have to ask the question.

What I'd rather see is something like this:

    COPY /v1/a1/c1/o1 HTTP/whatever
    Destination-Account: a2
    Destination: /c2/o2

That way the Destination-Account header's value is actually an account, and clients can't express two different destinations within a single request.

Alternately, something like this:

    COPY /v1/a1/c1/o1 HTTP/whatever
    Destination: /a2/c2/o2
    Destination-Includes-Account: yes

Neither one of those are pretty APIs, but I don't think we can get to "pretty" without a time machine.'}, {'account_id': 1216, 'date': '2014-02-10 19:02:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'm cool with any of these answers, with a small preference to Destination-Account and X-Copy-From-Account."}, {'account_id': 1216, 'date': '2014-02-10 19:04:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Er, sorry, that was completely ambiguous. :P I mean a small preference to account only in the new header, which then uses the /container/object from the original header, rather than possible duplication or conflicting /account/container/object in the new headers.'}, {'account_id': 5410, 'date': '2014-02-10 19:08:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Samuel: we can do "pretty" if we go /v2 path.
I'm just reusing an already existing code I had for quite some time in ZeroVM Swift fork. Yes, it's ugly, but it works, and I really consider X-Copy-From/Destination deprecated here.

But on the other hand I do like the second approach:
Destination-Account: a
Destination: /c/o 

Let's see what I can do here.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-02-10 19:10:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

So I think we are getting there....  But I ran into an issue.

On an SAIO I ran the following commands:

# Just upload a file
swiftly -A http://127.0.0.1:8080/auth/v1.0 -U test:tester -K testing put /test
swiftly -A http://127.0.0.1:8080/auth/v1.0 -U test:tester -K testing put /test/test -i ~/test

# test copy without perms
swiftly -A http://127.0.0.1:8080/auth/v1.0 -U test2:tester2 -K testing2 put -e /test
swiftly -A http://127.0.0.1:8080/auth/v1.0 -U test2:tester2 -K testing2 put -e /test/test2 -h "X-Copy-From: /test/test" -h "X-Copy-From-Account: test"

Returns a 403 Forbidden, which is great! :)

# test copy with perms
swiftly -A http://127.0.0.1:8080/auth/v1.0 -U test:tester -K testing put -e /test/test2 -h "X-Copy-From: /test/test" -h "X-Copy-From-Account: test"

Also returns a 403 Forbidden, which it shouldn't?  I'm not sure if this is maybe because the original account and the account I'm copying from is the same?

Also, I tried to look, but couldn't find any tests for the security bits.  If they are there, and I just missed them, then cool, but just wanted to make sure there were some in there.

Thanks, and hang in there :)'}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2014-04-02 15:22:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

commit_message:
account to account copy implementation

Adds ability to copy objects between different accounts (on server side)

Adds new header to `PUT` request:
`X-Copy-From-Account: <account name>`
Account name corresponds to the last part of storage URL.

Adds new header to `COPY` request:
`Destination-Account: <account name>`
Account name corresponds to the last part of storage URL.

If your storage URL is: http://server:8080/v1/AUTH_test
Then the account name is `AUTH_test`

These headers should be used alongside `X-Copy-From` and `Destination` headers
The legacy headers should specify `<container name>/<object name>` path as usual.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I0285fe6a47df9e699ac20ae4a83b0bf23829e1e6

[{'created': '2014-10-14 23:32:39.000000000', 'message': 'Collector which does a simple HTTP GET

commit_message:
Collector which does a simple HTTP GET

This change implements a collector which does an HTTP GET via
python requests to fetch the metadata.

It should work with any GET-able URL, however it is designed to
work with Swift TempURLs.

Swift objects are not consistent, so the Last-Modified header is
checked for each poll and metadata is not fetched if the last
modified is not newer than the previous successful poll.

This collector will be enabled for OS::Nova::Server
software_config_transport: POLL_TEMP_URL which is available
in the Juno release of Heat. Using POLL_TEMP_URL will result
in no metadata polling load on heat, which has historically been
an issue with tripleo scalability.

Change-Id: I22155c22bdcc3c81a5e945ca5436a8f29f196528

commit_message:
Adds svc-map to cinder elements

This patch changes the use of map-services to svc-map for the
cinder-tgt and cinder-volume elements.

Change-Id: I58da499d723957534d022112e261e20bff0c9e67

commit_message:
Make pci_requests a proper field on Instance object

When we added the pci_requests object, we didn't plumb it all the way into the
Instance object because of time constraints. This finishes that work so that it
behaves properly and doesn't require an additional DB lookup every time we need to
pull it based on an instance.

Partial-Bug: #1368260
Change-Id: I134441c8288d5dbdc0bac6163cb2affc9f0af762

commit_message:
Adds encapsulation control to the client

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/108795/ adds the requirement
to encapsulate messages in JSON objects in API v1.1

This change adds that control to the Zaqar client maintaining
backwards compatibility with v1

Change-Id: I1723b843320ebcf2722fb4f6fcaaa6e1c63248e9

commit_message:
Allow mock-based patching in shell tests

Added `patch` method that uses mock.patch (similar to `patchobject`)
  - NOTE: this shadows `testtools.TestCase.patch` method that uses
    simple monkey-patching in favor of mock-based patching,
    relevant comment added in the code.
Also oslotest dependency is added.

Change-Id: Ie4d25bc53decb308398eded350c81a90a257b254
Related-Bug: #1384511

commit_message:
Fix and re-enable test_disassociate_not_associated_floating_ip

Fixes test_disassociate_not_associated_floating_ip so it sets the
ec2_client class variable needed by a base class correctly. There
has been some bit-rot since it was disabled.

Note that this test will not pass until the nova fix
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/124320/ has merged.

Change-Id: Ice39358f4e8123334f24056daede68bead59729b
Related-Bug: 1179816

commit_message:
Split out PCI passthrough filter unit tests

Breaks out the PCI passthrough filter unit tests from
test_host_filters.py into their own test file, and uncrufts from stubout
to mock in the process.

Change-Id: I40bc7ae1a691b447b18cc75b9f615f3f7435988f

commit_message:
Convert authentication into a plugin

Extract all the information that is related to auth and make it into a
keystoneclient auth plugin. This will make it easier later to substitute
this auth plugin for another auth plugin.

Blueprint: pluggable-auth
Change-Id: Ibf9bc1dbf26f396bac09a96398a6467afc30f529

I asked around (not very widely) and was told that the usual variable to use in openstack was 'x' since '_' wasn't ok with gettext.  If there's some other convention in use let me know (I don't see 'dummy' used anywhere in neutron).

As you can see, I've added 'x' to the pylint config with this change so there's no need for us to change our practices to meet the pylint default."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-29 04:38:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

enikanorov: yeah, I hear you.
I did find 3 real bugs while preparing this change however (fixed in other changes so they don't get confused/block on this change), so I think there's more here than just making the checker happy and I'd like to find a way to keep both readability _and_ additional code checks if we can :)

An alternative would be to allow an "unused_" prefix (eg: "unused_router_id") - or perhaps something less verbose.  Does that sound better?  Do you have a good suggest for a suitable prefix (I think just a single underscore as some of the existing code was using is too ambiguous)?'}, {'account_id': 11279, 'date': '2014-08-29 05:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sorry to be late to the bike shedding party. :-) 

I don't like 'unused' because it sounds descriptive of what the variable contains (e.g. unused_old_floatingips) makes me think that the code returns floating IPs not in use.

Is it possible to just have pylint ignore unused variables assigned in for loops? That would eliminate most of the problems and then we can make the skip prefix really ugly like NOQA_"}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2014-09-14 10:23:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Whoops. My last message had an early close parenthesis. That second paragraph should have read:

I don't like 'unused' because it sounds descriptive of what the variable contains (e.g. unused_old_floatingips makes me think that the code returns floating IPs not in use)."}, {'account_id': 11279, 'date': '2014-09-15 02:25:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Yep s/unused/NOQA/ is just fine by me (and is shorter, which is nice).  I'll upload that version shortly.

I'd rather not just whitelist all for loop variables, since you can see from this change that a large number of cases were times when items() was used but keys() or values() was what was intended (same result but wastes memory and possibly DB operations, etc fetching the unused values).

Also note that I've already moved any real bugfixes out into separate changes, so this particular change by definition only includes the "boring" cases resulting from this exercise.'}, {'account_id': 11279, 'date': '2014-09-15 03:42:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-15 04:55:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

I'm not going to block it, but I think we could all be spending our time more productively."}, {'account_id': 11279, 'date': '2014-10-15 23:51:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Maru: Fwiw, I agree.  I expected a pretty straightforward no-op change like this to be uncontroversial and quickly approved/submitted.  I never suspected it would turn into a multiple-month ordeal involving such a large number of reviewers.  I'm learning :P

The bigger picture here is that I think openstack is an unusually large python project, and neutron (in particular) has an unusually diverse set of contributors working across separate portions of the code.  Given that, I think it is very important to take advantage of tools that can automatically perform cross-code verification, help maintain common standards, and automatically catch errors early in the development cycle.  After surveying several alternatives, I concluded that although pylint doesn't have the nicest UI, it has the most suitable underlying technology to build upon.

To that end, I have a series of patches to introduce pylint checking to neutron.  This is one of the most boring, since I deliberately moved any actual bugs discovered during the unused-vars cleanup into separate changes (from memory there were 2).

I assure you that I too am eager to just get these changes reviewed by cores and move on to something else."}, {'account_id': 11279, 'date': '2014-10-16 00:08:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-28 23:22:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2014-10-28 23:28:38.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

I think this has got to be handled differently.  I also agree with Maru, I think we've got higher priorities than this."}, {'account_id': 11279, 'date': '2014-10-29 00:54:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Carl: Any concrete suggestions for "differently"?
I get that this change isn't a priority, but it seems like we're making our code quality reflect our review process rather than the other way around :-(

I'd like to get the _ -> __ changes in, since they're a potential bug as soon as someone adds an i18n string later in the same function - so I'll try that as a separate change and see if that is acceptable.'}]

commit_message:
Remove several unused variables

Rename placeholder "_" variables to "__" (double-underscore) to avoid
conflict with gettext internationalisation function, and bless this
usage of "__" in pylintrc.

Rename unused-but-descriptive variables to "_foo" (leading-underscore)
and bless this prefix in pylintrc.

Enable unused-variable pylint check.

Change-Id: Ib9dff7d811532ec9791368f5864b2aae1bf80f8b

commit_message:
Fix borders for "Actions" column in Firefox

Added 'background-clip:padding-box' to "Actions" column
styling to make its borders visible in Firefox. Moreover,
since not every table has odd/even classes for its rows,
there still are some issues with border colors for a few
tables. This patch set adds 'background-clip:padding-box'
to each row style (not only to odd rows) to make borders
visible for every row, "Actions" column in Firefox.

Closes-bug: 1384116

Change-Id: Ibc540fd62bd918c0a5a70c410a16d8af86bedcfa

commit_message:
Remove templates from toctrees

We don't want the templates to show up in the RSS feed, so exclude them
from being converted to HTML and listed in the toctree.

Remove the now unused index.rst.

Change-Id: I28c02aff7a8d34ae6c5749c3cd8214a90ba593f3

commit_message:
TEST: See why fatal_deprecations isn't working

fatal_deprecations should make nova die in a fire if something goes
wrong. This isn't happening, testing why.

Change-Id: I0432a44230c330d349f31e39ccad7ab810f5847c

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Remove useless use of "else" clause on for loop

"else" on for loops is only important if the loop contains a "break"
statement.  Without a "break", the else block is _always_ executed and
it is clearer just to omit "else".

This change also enables the corresponding pylint warning, now that the
only offending case has been fixed.

Change-Id: Ibe8761cb40a7d2d564aa718d62c9f383b5ad711e

commit_message:
Log exceptions in drivers

The previous version would catch all Exceptions and then ignore them.
This made it difficult to notice problems in the datasource drivers.
This change adds the exception and backtrace to the log.

Change-Id: I7f93c15e6c8d37f9495d5005b52809d01c46ccdd

commit_message:
Clear state later in ceilometer driver

The previous version cleared self.state before update_from_datasource() was
finished using self.state.  This caused KeyError failures when the ceilometer
data stays the same.  This change clears self.state after
update_from_datasource() is finished using it.

Change-Id: I97df021b6036c5d80bc2c7f97f5dba8ebbd0dd38

commit_message:
Brick LVM: Optimize get_volume

When we only want the LV information for a single volume, call
"lvs" with the volume name specified.

This should reduce unnecessary load of calling "lvs" for the
whole VG.

Related-Bug: #1373513

Change-Id: Ifbb679e9160f44fe52ecba7bf19aa0eb5bb133f1

commit_message:
Return eye-icon to its place when validation message is shown

Making eye-icon properly positioned relies on its parent having
'has-feedback' class - which makes the parent to obey 'position:
relative' and thus eye-icon with its 'position: absolute' is properly
positioned within it.

Change-Id: I69ce13e1e3fc9674c4f25e7d04d79a3f550014a6
Closes-Bug: #1386126

commit_message:
Fix misleading  message in Update Metadata Form.

First you put some data to Other field.
In next step you delete it.
Then you give message 'invalid key name'.
This is inconsistent to this field behavior.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1371230

Change-Id: I61d3569adf89277ddec61507bd7816513e4623eb

commit_message:
NSX: allow multiple networks with same vlan on different phy_net

Previously, the NSX plugin prevented one from creating multiple networks on
the same vlan even if they were being created on different physical_networks.
This patch corrects this issue and allows this to now occur.

Closes-bug: 1367034
