commit_message:
TripleO DVR enablement

Outline for means to add the ability to configure enablement
of neutron distributed routers in the overcloud.

Added 'kilo' folder for this spec.

Change-Id: I52f213c794bc008c9b0a0fbcb4464cba9f309801

Fixes typo - liaison was misspelled in template

liaison was misspelled as liasion in the template. This patch fixes
 the same.

commit_message:
Add CORS middleware for OpenStack APIs to use.

This adds middleware that OpenStack APIs may use to enable cross-origin
access by browser-based Javascript clients.

This work is partially based off a previous change 21958, though it
deviates from that work in a number of ways:

1. integrates with configuration,
2. does not implement that change's extensions to the CORS spec (HTTP
   unauthorized responses), and
3. has a simpler factory setup.

Change-Id: Iecfdd9f0fe45f1e7d61dee0a4763f253dceac11a
Closes-Bug: 987044

[{'created': '2014-10-28 15:01:43.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes DOS issue in instance list ip filter

Converts the ip filtering to filter the list locally based
on the network info cache instead of making an extremely expensive
call over to nova network where it attempts to retrieve a list
of every instance in the system.

Change-Id: I455f6ab4acdecacc5152b11a183027f933dc4475
Closes-bug: #1358583
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes DOS issue in instance list ip filter

Converts the ip filtering to filter the list locally based
on the network info cache instead of making an extremely expensive
call over to nova network where it attempts to retrieve a list
of every instance in the system.

Change-Id: I455f6ab4acdecacc5152b11a183027f933dc4475
Closes-bug: #1358583

commit_message:
Adds requirement of 'Reviewers' to the specs

This patch adds "Reviewers" subsection under the "Implementation"
section in the template. Thus, all the specs following this commit
would need to suffice the Reviewers requirement for the approval.
Email [0] sent to the ML, corresponding to this requirement.

[0] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-October/048918.html

Change-Id: I396b7fad247a2e115bf9c7b7634240c15355ab20

commit_message:
NetApp fix for default host type in eseries

This fixes the issue where the default host type
provided in mapping should be high performing LnxALUA
type for eseries. It also makes it configurable in case
users want to configure a different host type.

Closes-Bug: #1365884

Change-Id: I30992ca69c25c3c02334470aae90c32731a5f3f4
(cherry picked from commit a120ede9ae3f18756db07d1d6696b9ac773b84bf)

commit_message:
Test patch to debug DVR jenkins failure

*** DO NOT MERGE ***

This is a test patch to help me debug a jenkins failure I'm seeing
with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123911 that I cannot
reproduce otherwise.  Just adding things back piece by piece until
I find what's causing the heat job grief.

Change-Id: I1e5b684c356358627b0c29d584fb533d73dea6b1

commit_message:
API for pools

This change adds apis for managing pools.
Currently the only attribute recognized is 'scope'.
name servers and attributes for a pool are specified
using the api.  pool_servers are specified in the
config file.

Change-Id: I2b4a19edc889167079ccc018a9a721da9aad6105
Implements: blueprint server-pools-api

I think the problem you're running into is that dictionary order is not guaranteed, so when the dictionary is turned into a 'string' you will not necessarily get the same order of elements.

In this case look at the order of 'Container-Foo' and 'Container-Bar' to see where they differ.

If you look at the Kilo version of the test that is failing, they are splitting the output and then sorting it before comparing it to get around this problem.

Currently, the fork_child() function in auditor.py does not
handle the case where run_audit() encounters an exception
properly.

A simple case is where the /srv directory is set
with permissions such that the 'swift' user cannot access it.
Such a situation causes a os.listdir() to return an OSError
exception.  When this happens the fork_child() process does not
run to completion and sys.exit() is not executed.  The process
that was forked off continues to run as a result.  Execution goes
back up to the audit_loop function which restarts the whole process.  The
end result is an increasing number of processes on the system
until the parent is terminated.  This can quickly exhaust the
process descriptors on a system.

This change wraps run_audit() in a try block and adds an
exception handler that prints what exception was encountered.
The sys.exit() was moved to a finally: block so that it will
always be run, avoiding the creation of zombies.

Change-Id: I89d7cd27112445893852e62df857c3d5262c27b3
Closes-bug: 1375348

commit_message:
Ensure sys.exit called in fork_child after exception

Currently, the fork_child() function in auditor.py does not
handle the case where run_audit() encounters an exception
properly.

A simple case is where the /srv directory is set
with permissions such that the 'swift' user cannot access it.
Such a situation causes a os.listdir() to return an OSError
exception.  When this happens the fork_child() process does not
run to completion and sys.exit() is not executed.  The process
that was forked off continues to run as a result.  Execution goes
back up to the audit_loop function which restarts the whole process.  The
end result is an increasing number of processes on the system
until the parent is terminated.  This can quickly exhaust the
process descriptors on a system.

This change wraps run_audit() in a try block and adds an
exception handler that prints what exception was encountered.
The sys.exit() was moved to a finally: block so that it will
always be run, avoiding the creation of zombies.

Change-Id: I89d7cd27112445893852e62df857c3d5262c27b3
Closes-bug: 1375348
(cherry picked from commit 301a96f664d58b4ccad8e3cbf5d5a889cc76790f)

commit_message:
Remove gettextutils

Since we have now moved to current oslo-incubator code, we can remove
the compatibility code from i18n.py and remove the dropped gettextutils
module from manila.

Adjust manila-share to use i18n code instead of gettextutils.

Change-Id: I5191a1ac068305aee2709b9565b6c1ca2da966a5

commit_message:
Service group and Service Object for firewall as a service

In the traditional firewall design a service is used to define type of traffic
in firewall. This blueprint creates an extension that allows the firewall
administrators to create customized service objects. The customized service
objects can be grouped together to form a service group object. The policy
rule of FWaaS can reference more than one type of traffic by referencing to
service group objects.
Implements: blueprint fwaas-customized-service for customized service
Change-Id: I1c6394a01dc29ffbc5eab815dd7019bb72435d38
Authored-by: badveli vishnuvardhan <badveli_vishnuus@yahoo.com>

commit_message:
Fix cmd_dsvm_gate_tests to run tests in dsvm gate

A few configuration workarounds are needed to be able to run the trove
int-tests as part of the dsvm-gate. Specifically:
- Updated the swift endpoint in the catalog to be reachable from the guest
- Updated the jenkins user to connect to the trove guest image as ubuntu
- Fixed the iptables rules that prevent amqp connections from the devstack
  box to the guests

Closes-Bug: 1386337
Change-Id: I2d2c24a7d4ca40c3ab37f37d2759aa97ac2ab95a

These scripts used to dump the credentials file into the CWD rather than $TRIPLEO_ROOT. When we changed to putting them in a predictable place, we left this code looking in the CWD to preserve behaviour for people who still had their passwords there.

This change would break backwards compatibility for those people. I'd like the commit message to explain why breaking backwards compatibility is required here.

In fact, I'd go further and say that the commit violates the first item at https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages#Information_in_commit_messages - it assumes that the review understands the problem being solved here.

Assuming that there's a good reason to break backwards compatibility, this change is still wrong. The seutp-*-passwords scripts implement their own checks to see whether the password file already exists; if it does, they will append new passwords to it but not trample on existing passwords. If I've understood the ternary operator correctly, this change would not run setup-*-passwords if there's already an existing file, which deprives setup-*-passwords of the chance to append new passwords.

If there's a good reason to break backwards compatibility and ignore credentials files in ., I believe we should get rid of the conditional entirely and simply call setup-*-passwords and let them decide what they need to do with the (maybe already existing, maybe not) credentials file."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-03 08:35:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

I think my -1 isn't showing up because patchset 2 was substantially different; it got the code to a point where it addressed all of my concerns except for backwards compatibility

I commented on Ifca80a1d9bc9aff61aee8c70e67f59451d1bb55b that I've now realised backwards compatibility might not be the biggest reason to vote this down; the current behaviour (and the behaviour proposed in that change) allow for someone running multiple stacks to maintain separate credentials for each stack. This change would require that each stack has its own $TRIPLEO_ROOT, which would then have its own copy of al of the code, tools, repos, images etc

As a counter to that point, I don't think we've yet found anyone who does actually run multiple stacks with seperate credentials for each.

Regardless - that change does everything this one does and more, so I'd suggest moving the discussion over to that change."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-08-22 06:03:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

commit_message:
Be paranoid about where devtest_(over|under)cloud look for creds.

Force devtest_undercloud.sh and devtest_overcloud to always look in
$TRIPLEO_ROOT for their credentials, instead of looking in whatever the
present working directory happens to be first.

Change-Id: I2f2a4ffd6ba790156ddadd37e5f60d1e7def2814

commit_message:
Get rid of misleading use of TRIPLEO_OS_DISTRO.

Per lifeless @ https://review.openstack.org/#/c/93745/,
TRIPLEO_OS_DISTRO refers to the distro that the build host is using, not
the the distro that the stack should wind up running (which is handled
via NODE_DIST).

Change-Id: I3f5234b4382deec4e3e92439034892f07efaa5b4

commit_message:
LioAdm: Delete initiator from targets on terminate_connection

In current LioAdm implementation, initiators are remained even if
terminate_connection is called. This keeps volumes exported to hosts
after instances attaching the volumes are live-migrated to another
host, which is not good for security. It also causes an error on the
migration back to the original host, because cinder-rtstool doesn't
update CHAP authentication if the initiator already exists.

With this patch, initiators are deleted on terminate_conection.
'initiator-delete' operation is added to cinder-rtstool.
It makes the following live-migration succeed.
Also, this adds unit tests for initialize_connection and
terminate_connection methods in LioAdm.

Change-Id: Ib273f0ba4f1ef553374c0433b049f18719f8c758
Closes-Bug: #1369541

[{'created': '2014-09-24 15:49:01.000000000', 'message': "Don't put the message payload into warning log

When a caller msg doesn't exists anymore but a reply is ready for it.
amqp driver drop the whole message into a logging.warn. That can be a
bit huge in some case.

and the messages into the debug level.

commit_message:
Don't put the message payload into warning log

When a caller msg doesn't exists anymore but a reply is ready for it.
amqp driver drop the whole message into a logging.warn. That can be a
bit huge in some case.

This change just writes the message id to the WARN level and put the queues
and the messages into the debug level.

Change-Id: Ibcc6b066171cdea48f102ca1bd85f81c639fbbb5

commit_message:
Add tests for nova datasource driver

This patch adds test coverage for the nova datasource driver
for the servers and flavors table. The floating_ips table at
this time does not seem to be working so that coverage will have
to be added later once that is fixed.

Closes-bug: 1376478

Change-Id: I6a57bd60c68808002bf78c700fd5ded610752ab2

commit_message:
Copy instance type info into instance metadata

This commit copy instance type info into instance metadata while
booting and successful resizing, so that user can retrieve instance
type data even the flavor is deleted or not accessable.

Change-Id: Ie14f206ef32fea4eff122c49269400adb91bc0a9

commit_message:
Clear maintenance_reason when setting maintenance=False

Automatically clear maintenance_reason when node.update is used
to set maintenance=False. This is to ensure backwards compatibility
with tools using the standard node.update mechanism, rather than
the new API endpoint), for setting maintenance mode.

Also adds a deprecation message to the node update API, if maintenance
is set via this API.

Change-Id: Ie24339239eecbd0b46d0ccddc09582df2aaa9d60
Implements: blueprint maintenance-reason
DocImpact

subject: Adds user friendly message when --segment-size is a non-integer

1. You might add a test directly on the SwiftService.upload method, like this [1], in addition to the test you have.
The reason I suggest this is that if this other patch [2] is approved then your current test will need to be removed or changed. (Note that even if [2] is approved your patch is necessary because code other than shell.py may be calling SwiftService with bad options.)

2. Would you consider extending your check for segment size = 0 or negative? (see test in [1], currently swiftclient will upload forever if segment size is 0). That could be a follow-on patch or added to this one.

commit_message:
lockutils-wrapper cleanup

There were a couple of issues with the lockutils wrapper.  Most
importantly, lockutils silently did nothing if it was called in the
same way as the old incubator lockutils module.  This had the
potential to cause problems when simply doing a find and replace to
migrate to oslo.concurrency.  The problem is fixed by making
lockutils raise an exception if it is called directly.

There was also a name mismatch in the docstring for the console
entry point, which is also fixed in this change.

Closes-Bug: 1386734
Change-Id: I8868820ca314eb8d6fee83cc66fea886c1e74e27

commit_message:
Add pbr to installation requirements

Add pbr to the list of installation requirements so that it is installed
via pip before this library is installed, instead of with easy_install.
This avoids issues like Bug #1384919, and ensures that projects that use
this library as a dependency are properly installed.

Change-Id: I6c155370dbd01fe4748d5137bdf288e8d3e1a67e

commit_message:
Add fuel plugin example

The plugin shows how user can create plugin
with packages, and deploy the packages on slaves.

Change-Id: I6bb272024bae920b48f936347829692503e8b07b
Implements: blueprint cinder-neutron-plugins-in-fuel

commit_message:
Server Pools Storage

 This partially implements the changes needed
 for server pools. Done is:
 - Added pools table
 - Added pool_attributes table
 - Added pool CRUD calls in central and storage
   with unit tests
 - Created default pool

 Still to do in separte patchset(s):
 - Add pool_id column to domains table and change
   necessary code
 - Migrate servers from servers table pool_
   attributes table and change necessary code
 - Remove all old server API code

 Partially-implements: blueprint server-pools-storage

Change-Id: I55cd2fab94cef0e72d4f6cac2b24734f24390711

commit_message:
Fpb, fix repo building for centos

Create repo generated wrong paths to packets when
we specified Packages directory, it thought that
packages were located in root directory of the
repository, it's not required to specify this
directory explicitly, and in this case createrepo
generates right paths to the packages.

Change-Id: I8742c3c37637a66b2f335bad32dfecea4f3ba9aa
Implements: blueprint cinder-neutron-plugins-in-fuel

commit_message:
Install openstackclient

KeystoneClient doesn't support keystone v3 operations.
They are now supported by openstackclient. In order to
use keystone v3 operations we need to have
python-openstackclient installed

Change-Id: I8112e387180aa88bc92d91e103ee958f7bf56b9a
Closes-bug: #1384838

commit_message:
JAH-775 Monasca-api is encountering SSL problems

Allow trustore and keystore to be configured

Allow adminToken to not be set as it is not required in password
mode authentication

Change-Id: I3a4049f51d2b984e539a18a6435a6eb0d78620d5

commit_message:
Fix OrderedDict usage for Python 2.6

"import collections" also works on Python 2.6 but
collections.OrderedDict() is not available so the current check is
wrong. Using a function to get an OrderedDict() instance works fine for
that.

Closes-Bug: #1375568
Change-Id: Iaf739dc2deb7d4b09bf477be60de4df8c4fcf5c0

commit_message:
Remove duplicated _fetch_images function

This patch removes the _fetch_images function from the agent driver and
changes the driver to use the identical function found in deploy_utils.py

Change-Id: Ic206258f65a88c0f7557b405c7de425cfd01900f
Closes-Bug: 1350594

Fix type in method name get_schema

This patch fixes a type in the method name get_schema which prevented
congress from starting if the cinder driver was loaded.

commit_message:
Get testenv docs working

I had to make some modifications to get the testenv docs working
in my environment.  Adding sphinx as a requirement and making
sure that tox loads the project dependencies.  Now I am able to
run tox -e docs.

commit_message:
Pin mccabe to prevent it from breaking hacking

mccabe has undergone some very significant bug fixes recently but has
not yet released a new version. When it does, complexity calculations
will change in potentially significant ways.

Cherry-picked onto 0.9.x to make sure a release of mccabe doesn't break
existing 0.9.x users.

Change-Id: I6e75391da19fde45588575517087d1ba4e4c44b7
(cherry picked from commit 7a649681f984f2a246eae23cd05d6973d14d5745)

commit_message:
Enable debug logging on seed via local collector

Including this element in a build will allow us to enable debug logging
on the seed by adding debug properties to the local data collector.

Please make sure this passes on the tripleo-ha job as this is the only
job run with --debug-logging.

Change-Id: I6cdd4a278e440d9794f2da933e5f873f018e838c

commit_message:
Improve snapshots list API filtering

1) Added new params for filtering by:
- source share
- usage of snapshot*
- limit and offset a la pagination
- direction (asc, desc)*
- key of snapshot*

* requires server-side update

2) Added aliases for params, mostly in perspective to avoid mess of underscore
and dash symbols.

Implements blueprint improve-snapshot-list-filtering

Change-Id: I3727911f179ea01dd4cb68149fa7f4d79ca75a5c

commit_message:
Use look up service for auto zoning

The VMAX FC driver didn't use the look up service for auto zoning.
Instead it built initiator target map itself. However, that
requires the initiator to log into the fabric before zoning
in order to find out target WWNs.

This patch is to use the look up service to find out valid initiator
target WWNS and use that to build initiator target map. With this fix,
the initiator is no longer required to log into the fabric ahead of time.

Change-Id: I76e1a8a2e7d4230b851b763f7d13dd1489b69364
Closes-Bug: #1379156

commit_message:
Correct use of noqa

The use of "#flake8: noqa" disables hacking checks for the entire
file. Switched to use of "# noqa" and fixed hacking problems.

Change-Id: I18785fb18bdce88e61e2451960e55aed0863c285

commit_message:
Make 101-tuskar-ui re-runnable

The checks that are added are:
* if a Tuskar overcloud plan already exists, skip the tuskar API
  calls
* do not update the openstack_dashboard settings if the specified
  settings are already present

Change-Id: Idedfd2dea2a823245e749ae27e40ae4e29639726

commit_message:
libvirt: fully parse PCI vendor/product IDs to integer data type

When parsing node device XML, the PCI vendor/product IDs were left
in their string form, which is unhelpful for later code wishing to
use their raw values. Fully parse them to the integer form instead.

Blueprint: virt-driver-get-available-resources-object
Change-Id: I46b9c33e08122eb7c28601752ecfc652e09175c1

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123578/1'}, {'account_id': 5660, 'date': '2014-09-29 13:03:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2014-10-27 18:47:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

This change is not necessary. You can run cleanup stuff prior to and after running d-g. Just add it to your jenkins jobs (which you would have to do to take advantage of this change anyways).

The reason we have the other hooks is you actually do want to run the test stuff in the context of d-g but site specific cleanup should be fine without that context.

Adding this functionality to d-g is also problematic because it will not be tested/consumed upstream which can lead to it breaking in unexpected ways.'}, {'account_id': 9624, 'date': '2014-10-28 16:58:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I was able to do what I needed without using the patch using Clark's suggestion.

Pre-clean, however, is not quite pre-clean, since it runs after devstack cleans. In my case, I was sanitizing log files, so in post-clean, I unzip them, update, and rezip them. Performance penalty to unzip and rezip is about 2 seconds, which is acceptible. 

e.g.

          cp devstack-gate/devstack-vm-gate-wrap.sh ./safe-devstack-vm-gate-wrap.sh
          set +e
          ./safe-devstack-vm-gate-wrap.sh
          job_result=$?

          export BASE=/opt/stack
          pre_clean_hook
          post_clean_hook

          exit $job_result

So I will abandon."}, {'account_id': 9624, 'date': '2014-10-28 16:58:46.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

I was able to do what I needed without using the patch using Clark's suggestion.

Pre-clean, however, is not quite pre-clean, since it runs after devstack cleans. In my case, I was sanitizing log files, so in post-clean, I unzip them, update, and rezip them. Performance penalty to unzip and rezip is about 2 seconds, which is acceptible. 

e.g.

          cp devstack-gate/devstack-vm-gate-wrap.sh ./safe-devstack-vm-gate-wrap.sh
          set +e
          ./safe-devstack-vm-gate-wrap.sh
          job_result=$?

          export BASE=/opt/stack
          pre_clean_hook
          post_clean_hook

          exit $job_result

So I will abandon."}]

commit_message:
Add a pre-clean and post-clean hooks.

3rd party ci needs to do some cleanup.
post_test_hook is not sufficient because it only runs when successful.
Existing cleanup host function doesn't have any hooks.
Let this be the hook.
While we're at it, let's add a post-clean hook for completeness.

Change-Id: Iade4870dbdec97b6bb9c407d1e200505dfc427ed

commit_message:
Fixes Facts string comparisons in CentOS 7

- CentOS Project has adopted a new rule for versioning numbers. The major number
  matches the RHEL major number, but the minor number is generated from the
  release date. For example, CentOS 7.0.1407.
- Adds Support for Scientific Linux.

Change-Id: I3220206aa01b9f5c838e524b3fec723c92435153
Closes-Bug: 1338777
Signed-off-by: Gael Chamoulaud <gchamoul@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit cca209f8b1fb37c611194030ba0701ab2a4134aa)

commit_message:
Use cinder API v2, remove support for v1

Cinder API v1 was deprecated in Juno and is being removed in Kilo.

Implements: blueprint horizon-cinder-v2-preferred-version
Closes-Bug: 1376424
Change-Id: I9bbdf1753a06d33b441a85ff448f475545eafc80
